# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: c-robert-kidder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] After significant financial losses in the early 1990s and a leveraged buyout by private equity firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts (KKR) in 1995, Borden divested itself of its various divisions, brands and businesses.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] KKR shut Borden's food products operations in 2001 and divested all its other Borden operations in 2005.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden dairy brands are currently used by Borden Dairy for milk and by Dairy Farmers of America for cheese.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The company was founded by Gail Borden Jr., in 1857 in Connecticut as "Gail Borden Jr., and Company." Its primary product was condensed milk.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Struggling financially, the company was saved when Jeremiah Milbank, a partner in the wholesale food distributor I. & R.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Milbank & Co. and the son-in-law of banker Joseph Lake, agreed to invest and acquired 50 percent of the stock.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The company changed its name in 1858 to the New York Condensed Milk Company.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The company prospered during the Civil War by selling condensed milk to Union armies.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden began selling processed milk to consumers in 1875 and pioneered the use of glass milk bottles in 1885.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden began selling evaporated milk in 1892, and expanded into Canada in 1895.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The company changed its name to "Borden's Condensed Milk Company" in 1899.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] It suffered a legal setback in 1912, when a federal appellate court held that the Borden Ice Cream Co.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] (a competitor whose ownership included one "Charles Borden") could sell ice cream under the Borden name because Borden's Condensed Milk sold only milk, not ice cream, but the limit on its products was short-lived.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] It became the Borden Company in 1919 and expanded rapidly, buying numerous dairies, ice cream manufacturers, cheese producers, and mincemeat processors.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Taking advantage of its many herds of cattle, the company became involved in rendering and the manufacture of adhesives.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In World War II, Borden pioneered the American manufacture of non-dairy creamer, instant coffee and powdered foods.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In 1929, Borden was reorganized as a holding company for four separate entities: Borden's Food Products Company, Inc., Borden's Dairy Products Company, Inc., Borden's Ice Cream and Milk Company, Inc., and Borden's Cheese & Produce Company, Inc.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] However, in 1936 its operations were reunified, and these subsidiaries became divisions.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden's fictitious spokesperson, Jane Ellison, was introduced in 1929.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The recipe for "Magic Lemon Cream Pie", the ancestor of the Key lime pie, is attributed to her, found in a Borden promotional brochure from 1931.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden and other dairy companies were investigated in 1938 for violations of the Sherman Antitrust Act, but the charges were dropped after Borden signed a consent decree in 1940.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden milk products in Canada began with condensed milk in Quebec and East Coast with headquarters in Montreal.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden's Canadian operational head office moved to Toronto in 1931 when it acquired City Dairy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The old City Dairy Stables on Spadina Crescent was renamed Borden Stables and now part of the University of Toronto.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden's Canadian operations slowly disappeared, with Quebec operations being sold to Agropur in 1976 and Ontario operations to Silverwood Dairy in 1980.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In the 1950s, Borden moved into the printing ink, fertilizer, and polyvinyl chloride (PVC) plastics business.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] By 1961, it was making 7 percent of all raw PVC in the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] By 1968, Borden's international chemical and petroleum divisions had grown so large that Borden created the Borden Inc.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The company owned the Danish company Cocio from 1976 to 1999.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In 1987, Borden spun off some of its chemicals business in a public offering.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden retained a small financial investment in the new company, known legally as Borden Chemicals & Plastics Operating Limited Partnership (BCPOLP).
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The food products division was spun off as Borden Food Corporation when Borden, Inc. became a holding company in 1929.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The holding company reversed itself 13 years later when it reacquired its child company.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Although Borden retrenched in the inflationary 1970s, it embarked on a second wave of mergers and acquisitions in the 1980s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] It purchased Coco López in 1978 and Guys Snack Foods in 1979.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] It also purchased the Prince pasta manufacturing concern (giving Borden 30 percent of the domestic pasta market).
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In 1986, it purchased the dairy products division of Beatrice Foods, including the Meadow Gold brand.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Stockholders blamed the company's decline on mismanagement, the incurrence of excessive debt to finance its numerous acquisitions, and several recent restructurings.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden suffered significant losses for the period 1991–1993.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] A 1991 restructuring failed to integrate the company's brands and marketing efforts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] When whole milk prices dropped in 1992, Borden Food did not lower its prices—causing a significant drop in market share from which it was not able to recover.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden divested itself of nearly a third of its businesses in 1993 but could not find a buyer for its snack food concerns.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In deep financial difficulty, Borden was bought out by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts (KKR) in 1995.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] KKR increased the pace of divestiture but was unable to right the company.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The company's Borden/Meadow Gold Dairies subsidiary was sold in September 1997 to Southern Foods, controlled by the Mid-America Dairymen (later the Dairy Farmers of America).
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden licensed the use of Elsie the Cow but retained ownership of the trademark.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Southern Foods was acquired by Suiza Foods (now Dean Foods).
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The dairies are now owned by Dean Foods and Borden Dairy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Dairy Farmers of America retains Borden cheese.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In 1997, KKR focused the company solely on its pasta and pasta sauces lines.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In June 2001, Borden Food sold several pasta lines to the American Italian Pasta Company and its pasta sauce and soup businesses (including Wyler's) to the H.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In July 2001, Borden Foods sold its remaining pasta lines to New World Pasta.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden, Inc., sold its final food product line, It's Pasta Anytime, to Kraft Foods in 2001 and shuttered its Foods division.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] With the chemicals business the sole remaining operating company, in 2001 KKR merged Borden, Inc. into Borden Chemical, Inc., with the resulting company named Borden Chemical to emphasize the fact that chemicals were the company's sole remaining product line.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] In 2004, KKR sold Borden Chemical to Apollo Management, a private equity firm.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden Chemical was merged with Resolution Performance Products, Resolution Specialty Materials, and the German firm Bakelite AG to form Hexion Specialty Chemicals.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] With the merger (which settled in 2005), the last vestige of Borden, Inc. ceased to exist except as spin-offs and brand names.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Hexion retained control over the Elsie the Cow trademarks and Borden name until Dec 2014 and has now assigned all Borden/Elsie trademarks in the U.S. to Grupo Lala of Durango, Mexico.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] Borden once operated a chain of ice cream stores called Borden's Ice Cream, but only a single location in Lafayette, Louisiana, remains, under local ownership.
[src:c-robert-kidder/borden-inc] The Borden Buildings (North Building 563 Spadina Crescent and South Building 487 Spadina Crescent) in Toronto were once home to Borden Canadian dairy operations (founded in 1900 by Walt Massey as City Dairy) and are now used by the University of Toronto.
[src:c-robert-kidder/c-robert-kidder] At the time of his appointment, Kidder was chairman and CEO of 3Stone Advisors LLC, an investment firm that focuses on clean-tech companies.
[src:c-robert-kidder/c-robert-kidder] Industrial Economics from Iowa State University and a B.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/c-robert-kidder] Industrial Engineering from the University of Michigan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/c-robert-kidder] Kidder is an alumnus of Lambda Chi Alpha fraternity, having been initiated at its Michigan chapter as an undergraduate.
[src:c-robert-kidder/c-robert-kidder] He resides with his family in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The original Chrysler Corporation was founded in 1925 by Walter Chrysler from the remains of the Maxwell Motor Company.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1998, it merged with Daimler-Benz, which renamed itself DaimlerChrysler but in 2007 sold off its Chrysler stake.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The company operated as Chrysler LLC through 2009, then as Chrysler Group LLC.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2014, it was acquired by Fiat S.p.A.; it subsequently operated as a subsidiary of the new Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA), then as a subsidiary of Stellantis, the company formed from the 2021 merger of FCA and PSA Group (Peugeot Société Anonyme).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] After founding the company, Walter Chrysler used General Motors (GM)'s brand diversification and hierarchy strategy that he knew of when he worked at its Buick division.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] He then acquired Fargo Trucks and the Dodge Brothers Company, and created the Plymouth and DeSoto brands in 1928.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Facing postwar declines in market share, productivity, and profitability, as GM and Ford were growing, Chrysler borrowed $250 million in 1954 from Prudential Insurance to pay for expansion and updated car designs.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler expanded into Europe by taking control of French, British, and Spanish auto companies in the 1960s; but in 1978 Chrysler Europe was sold to PSA Peugeot Citroën for a nominal $1.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The company struggled to adapt to changing markets, increased U.S. import competition, and safety and environmental regulation in the 1970s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] It began an engineering partnership with Mitsubishi Motors, and began selling Mitsubishi vehicles branded as Dodge and Plymouth in North America.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On the verge of bankruptcy in the late 1970s, it was saved by $1.5 billion in loan guarantees from the U.S. government.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] New CEO Lee Iacocca was credited with returning the company to profitability in the 1980s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1985, Diamond-Star Motors was created, further expanding the Chrysler-Mitsubishi relationship.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1987, Chrysler acquired American Motors Corporation (AMC), which brought the profitable Jeep, as well as the newly formed Eagle, brands under the Chrysler umbrella.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1998, Chrysler merged with German automaker Daimler-Benz to form DaimlerChrysler AG; the merger proved contentious with investors.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] As a result, Chrysler was sold to Cerberus Capital Management and renamed Chrysler LLC in 2007.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Like the other Big Three automobile manufacturers, Chrysler was affected by the automotive industry crisis of 2008–2010.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The company remained in business through a combination of negotiations with creditors, filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization on April 30, 2009, and participating in a bailout from the U.S. government through the Troubled Asset Relief Program.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On June 10, 2009, Chrysler emerged from the bankruptcy proceedings with the United Auto Workers pension fund, Fiat S.p.A., and the U.S. and Canadian governments as principal owners.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The bankruptcy resulted in Chrysler defaulting on over $4 billion in debts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In May 2011, Chrysler finished repaying its obligations to the U.S. government five years early, although the cost to the American taxpayer was $1.3 billion.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Over the next few years, Fiat S.p.A. gradually acquired the other parties' shares.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In January 2014, Fiat acquired the rest of Chrysler from the United Auto Workers retiree health trust, making Chrysler Group a subsidiary of Fiat S.p.A.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In May 2014, Fiat Chrysler Automobiles was established by merging Fiat S.p.A. into the company.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler Group LLC remained a subsidiary until December 15, 2014, when it was renamed FCA US LLC, to reflect the Fiat-Chrysler merger.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] As a result of the merger between FCA and PSA, on 17 January 2021 it became a subsidiary of the Stellantis Group.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Chrysler company was founded by Walter Chrysler on June 6, 1925, when the Maxwell Motor Company (est.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] 1904) was re-organized into the Chrysler Corporation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The company was headquartered in the Detroit enclave of Highland Park, where it remained until completing the move to its present Auburn Hills location in 1996.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler had arrived at the ailing Maxwell-Chalmers company in the early 1920s, hired to overhaul the company's troubled operations (after a similar rescue job at the Willys-Overland car company).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In late 1923, production of the Chalmers automobile was ended.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In January 1924, Walter Chrysler launched the well-received Chrysler automobile.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Chrysler Six was designed to provide customers with an advanced, well-engineered car, at an affordable price.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Elements of this car are traceable to a prototype which had been under development at Willys during Chrysler's tenure The original 1924 Chrysler included a carburetor air filter, high compression engine, full pressure lubrication, and an oil filter, features absent from most autos at the time.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Among the innovations in its early years were the first practical mass-produced four-wheel hydraulic brakes, a system nearly completely engineered by Chrysler with patents assigned to Lockheed, and rubber engine mounts, called "Floating Power" to reduce vibration.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler also developed a wheel with a ridged rim, designed to keep a deflated tire from flying off the wheel.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] This wheel was eventually adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Maxwell brand was dropped after the 1925 model year, with the new, lower-priced four-cylinder Chryslers introduced for the 1926 year being badge-engineered Maxwells.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The advanced engineering and testing that went into Chrysler Corporation cars helped to push the company to the second-place position in U.S. sales by 1936, which it held until 1949.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1928, the Chrysler Corporation began dividing its vehicle offerings by price class and function.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Plymouth brand was introduced at the low-priced end of the market (created essentially by once again reworking and rebadging the Chrysler Series 50 four-cylinder model).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] At the same time, the DeSoto brand was introduced in the medium-price field.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Also in 1928, Chrysler bought the Dodge Brothers automobile and truck company and continued the successful Dodge line of automobiles and Fargo range of trucks.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] By the mid-1930s, the DeSoto and Dodge divisions would trade places in the corporate hierarchy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Imperial name had been used since 1926 but was never a separate make, just the top-of-the-line Chrysler.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] However, in 1955, the company decided to offer it as its own make/brand and division to better compete with its rivals, Lincoln and Cadillac.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] This addition changed the company's traditional four-make lineup to five (in order of price from bottom to top): Plymouth, Dodge, DeSoto, Chrysler, and the now-separate Imperial.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On April 28, 1955, Chrysler and Philco announced the development and production of the World's First All-Transistor car radio.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The all-transistor car radio, Mopar model 914HR, developed and produced by Chrysler and Philco, was a $150 option on the 1956 Imperial automobile models.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Philco began manufacturing this radio in the fall of 1955 at its Sandusky Ohio plant.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On September 28, 1957, Chrysler announced the first production electronic fuel injection (EFI), as an option on some of its new 1958 car models (Chrysler 300D, Dodge D500, DeSoto Adventurer, Plymouth Fury).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The first attempt to use this system was by American Motors on the 1957 Rambler Rebel.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Bendix Corporation's Electrojector used a transistor "computer brain" modulator box, but teething problems on pre-production cars meant very few cars were made.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The EFI system in the Rambler ran fine in warm weather, but suffered hard starting in cooler temperatures and AMC decided not to use this EFI system on its 1957 Rambler Rebel production cars that were sold to the public.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler also used the Bendix "Electrojector" fuel injection system and only around 35 vehicles were built with this option, on its 1958 production-built car models.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Owners of EFI Chryslers were so dissatisfied that all but one were retrofitted with carburetors (while that one has been completely restored, with original EFI electronic problems resolved).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Valiant was also introduced for the 1960 model year as a distinct brand.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In the U.S. market, Valiant was made a model in the Plymouth line for 1961 and the DeSoto make was discontinued in 1961.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] With those exceptions per applicable year and market, Chrysler's range from lowest to highest price from the 1940s through the 1970s was Valiant, Plymouth, Dodge, DeSoto, Chrysler, and Imperial.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1954, Chrysler was the exclusive provider of its Hemi V8 engine in the Facel Vega, a French coachbuilder that offered its own line of hand-built luxury performance cars, coupled with the PowerFlite and TorqueFlite automatic transmissions.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Facel Vega Excellence was a four-door hardtop with rear-hinged coach doors that listed for US$12,800 ($142,837 in 2025 dollars ).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1960 Facel Vega introduced the smaller Facellia sports car to capitalize on its sales success with Chrysler supplied engines.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] At the time, Chrysler didn't produce a four-cylinder engine, and the company had to find alternatives before production began.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] From 1963 through 1969, Chrysler increased its existing stakes to take complete control of the French Simca, British Rootes, and Spanish Barreiros companies, merging them into Chrysler Europe in 1967.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In the 1970s, an engineering partnership was established with Mitsubishi Motors, and Chrysler began selling Mitsubishi vehicles branded as Dodge and Plymouth in North America.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler struggled to adapt to the changing environment of the 1970s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] When consumer tastes shifted to smaller cars in the early 1970s, particularly after the 1973 oil crisis, Chrysler could not meet the demand, although its compact models on the "A" body platform, the Dodge Dart and Plymouth Valiant, had proven economy and reliability and sold very well.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Additional burdens came from increased US import competition, and tougher government regulation of car safety, fuel economy, and emissions.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] As the smallest of the Big 3 US automakers, Chrysler lacked the financial resources to meet all of these challenges.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] 1975 would be the last year for Imperial, except for an ill-fated attempt at revival in 1981-1983, for its low sales no longer justified it as a separate brand when it didn't offer much over a high-end Chrysler New Yorker.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1976, with the demise of the reliable Dart/Valiant, quality control declined.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Their replacements, the Dodge Aspen and Plymouth Volare, were comfortable and had good roadability, but owners soon experienced major reliability problems which crept into other models as well.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Engines failed and/or did not run well, and premature rust plagued bodies.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1978, Lee Iacocca was brought in to turn the company around, and in 1979 Iacocca sought US government help.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Congress later passed the *Loan Guarantee Act* providing $1.5 billion in loan guarantees.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Also in 1978, Iacocca offloaded the ailing European operation to PSA Peugeot Citroën for a nominal $1, taking with it the group's substantial losses and debts which had been dragging the rest of the business down.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler returned to profitability in 1980, repaying the loans with interest in 1983.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Omni/Horizon were first offered with four-cylinder engines provided by Chrysler Europe brand Simca, then Volkswagen, until the all-new Chrysler engineered Chrysler K engine arrived.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler had not manufactured a four-cylinder engine since 1933 when the Chrysler flathead four-cylinder was canceled.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In November 1983, the Dodge Caravan/Plymouth Voyager was introduced, built on a modified K platform, establishing the minivan as a major category, and initiating Chrysler's return to stability.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1985, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors Corporation to produce Chrysler M platform rear-drive, as well as Dodge Omnis front wheel drive cars, in AMC's Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1987, Chrysler acquired the 47% ownership of AMC that was held by Renault.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The remaining outstanding shares of AMC were bought on the NYSE by August 5, 1987, making the deal valued somewhere between US$1.7 billion and US$2 billion, depending on how costs were counted.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted the Jeep brand, particularly the Jeep Grand Cherokee (ZJ) that was under development, the new world-class manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, and AMC's engineering and management talent that became critical for Chrysler's future success.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler established the Jeep/Eagle division as a "specialty" arm to market products distinctly different from the K-car-based products with the Eagle cars targeting import buyers.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Former AMC dealers sold Jeep vehicles and various new Eagle models, as well as Chrysler products, strengthening the automaker's retail distribution system.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Eurostar, a joint venture between Chrysler and Steyr-Daimler-Puch, began producing the Chrysler Voyager in Austria for European markets in 1992.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1998, Chrysler and its subsidiaries entered into a partnership dubbed a "merger of equals" with German-based Daimler-Benz AG, creating the combined entity DaimlerChrysler AG.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] To the surprise of many stockholders, Daimler acquired Chrysler in a stock swap before Chrysler CEO Bob Eaton retired.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Under DaimlerChrysler, the company was named DaimlerChrysler Motors Company LLC, with its U.S. operations generally called "DCX".
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Eagle brand was retired soon after Chrysler's merger with Daimler-Benz in 1998 Jeep became a stand-alone division, and efforts were made to merge the Chrysler and Jeep brands as one sales unit.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2001, the Plymouth brand was also discontinued.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Eurostar also built the Chrysler PT Cruiser in 2001 and 2002.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Austrian venture was sold to Magna International in 2002 and became Magna Steyr.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Voyager continued in production until 2007, whereas the Chrysler 300C, Jeep Grand Cherokee, and Jeep Commander were also built at the plant from 2005 until 2010.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On May 14, 2007, DaimlerChrysler announced the sale of 80.1% of Chrysler Group to American private equity firm Cerberus Capital Management, L.P., thereafter known as Chrysler LLC, although Daimler (renamed as Daimler AG) continued to hold a 19.9% stake.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The economic collapse during the 2008 financial crisis pushed the company to the brink.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On April 30, 2009, the automaker filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection to be able to operate as a going concern, while renegotiating its debt structure and other obligations, which resulted in the corporation defaulting on over $4 billion in secured debts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The U.S. government described the company's action as a "prepackaged surgical bankruptcy".
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On June 10, 2009, substantially all of Chrysler's assets were sold to "New Chrysler", organized as Chrysler Group LLC.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The federal government provided support for the deal with US$8 billion in financing at nearly 21%.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Under CEO Sergio Marchionne, "World Class Manufacturing" or WCM, a system of thorough manufacturing quality, was introduced and several products were re-launched with quality and luxury.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Ram, Jeep, Dodge, SRT, and Chrysler divisions were separated to focus on their own identity and brand, and 11 major model refreshes occurred in 21 months.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The PT Cruiser, Nitro, Liberty and Caliber models (created during DCX) were discontinued.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On May 24, 2011, Chrysler repaid its $7.6 billion loans to the United States and Canadian governments.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The US Treasury, through the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP), invested $12.5 billion in Chrysler and recovered $11.2 billion when the company shares were sold in May 2011, resulting in a $1.3 billion loss.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On July 21, 2011, Fiat bought the Chrysler shares held by the US Treasury.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The purchase made Chrysler foreign-owned again, this time as the luxury division.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Chrysler 300 was badged Lancia Thema in some European markets (with additional engine options), giving Lancia a much-needed replacement for its flagship.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On January 21, 2014, Fiat bought the remaining shares of Chrysler owned by the VEBA worth $3.65 billion.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Several days later, the intended reorganization of Fiat and Chrysler under a new holding company, Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA), together with a new logo were announced.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The most challenging launch for this new company came immediately in January 2014 with a completely redesigned Chrysler 200.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The vehicle's creation is from the completely integrated company, FCA, executing from a global compact-wide platform.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On December 16, 2014, Chrysler Group LLC announced a name change to FCA US LLC.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On January 12, 2017, FCA shares traded at the New York Stock Exchange lost value after the EPA accused FCA US of using emissions cheating software to evade diesel-emissions tests, however the company countered the accusations, and the chairman and CEO Sergio Marchionne sternly rejected them.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The following day, shares rose as investors played down the effect of the accusations.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Analysts gave estimates of potential fines from several hundred million dollars to $4 billion, although the likelihood of a hefty fine was low.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Senior United States Senator Bill Nelson urged the FTC to look into possible deceptive marketing of the company's diesel-powered SUVs.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Shares dropped 2.2% after the announcement.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] FCA US would in 2022, plead guilty to a criminal charge of conspiring to defraud the US, to wire fraud, and to violate the Clean Air Act.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On July 21, 2018, Sergio Marchionne stepped down as chairman and CEO for health reasons, and was replaced by John Elkann and Michael Manley, respectively.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] It was again fined for the 2017 model year for not meeting the minimum domestic passenger car standard.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The company was also to pay affected consumers up to $280 million and offer extended warranties on such vehicles worth $105 million.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The total value of the settlement was about $800 million, though FCA did not admit liability, and it did not resolve an ongoing criminal investigation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On December 21, 2020, the European Commission approved the merger between FCA and PSA Group with minimal conditions.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Shareholders approved the deal on January 4, 2021, and the merger was finalized on January 16, 2021, with FCA US now part of a new entity: Stellantis.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Stellantis shares began trading under the symbol “STLA” on the Milan Stock Exchange and Euronext Paris on January 18, followed by the New York Stock Exchange on January 19, and on the New York Stock Exchange on 19 January.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] For accounting purposes, PSA was designated the acquirer, and financial statements reflect PSA's historical performance.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Under Carlos Tavares' leadership, Stellantis faced growing criticism over its cost-cutting strategy, declining sales, and strained relations with key stakeholders.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Tavares implemented aggressive restructuring measures, including job cuts and strict control over product development, which some analysts blamed for delays in launching new models and weakening brand performance, particularly at Stellantis North America.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] U.S. dealers expressed concern about rising inventories and brand mismanagement, while the United Auto Workers criticized the company over job cuts and halted investment plans.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2024, Stellantis reported a 70% drop in net profit, with global shipments and U.S. market share declining significantly.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Amid internal friction with the board and worsening financial performance, Tavares resigned in December 2024, two years before his contract was set to expire.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On May 28, 2025, the board of Stellantis unanimously appointed Antonio Filosa, a longtime executive who had led Stellantis operations in North and South America, as CEO starting June 23.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Filosa is expected to place renewed emphasis on the North American market.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] However, the majority of its management team remains based in Europe.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Following the appointment of Filosa, formerly COO of Stellantis North America, Stellantis announced on June 10, 2025, that he would be based in Auburn Hills, Michigan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] His predecessor, Carlos Tavares, former CEO of PSA, was based in Europe and regularly worked remotely from his Portuguese property.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] He was considered by some to have insufficient presence in the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On October 14, 2025, Stellantis announced an investment of $13 billion to strengthen its growth in the United States over the next four years.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The company claims this is its largest investment in its century-long history in the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Belvidere, Illinois, plant will reopen for production of two new Jeep Cherokee and Jeep Compass vehicles.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The company also said it will create more than 5,000 manufacturing jobs in four Midwestern U.S. states.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] On May 20, 2026, Stellantis and British luxury carmaker Jaguar Land Rover signed a memorandum of understanding to "explore synergies in areas such as product and technology development" within the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Stellantis is the smallest of the "Big Three", which also includes Ford and GM.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2020, it sold just over 1.8 million vehicles.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler was the world's 11th largest vehicle manufacturer as ranked by OICA in 2012.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Total Chrysler vehicle production was about 2.37 million that year.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The company has since become a wholly owned subsidiary and no longer reports global sales.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2007, Chrysler began to offer vehicle lifetime powertrain warranty for the first registered owner or retail lessee.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The deal covered owner or lessee in U.S., Puerto Rico, and the Virgin Islands, for 2009 model year vehicles, and 2006, 2007, and 2008 model year vehicles purchased on or after July 26, 2007.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Covered vehicles excluded SRT models, Diesel vehicles, Sprinter models, Ram Chassis Cab, Hybrid System components (including transmission), and certain fleet vehicles.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] After Chrysler's restructuring, the warranty program was replaced by five-year/100,000 mile transferable warranty for 2010 or later vehicles.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2008, as a response to customer feedback citing the prospect of rising gas prices as a top concern, Chrysler launched the "Let's Refuel America" incentive campaign, which guaranteed new-car buyers a gasoline price of $2.99 for three years.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] With the U.S. purchase of eligible Chrysler, Jeep, and Dodge vehicles, customers could enroll in the program and receive a gas card that immediately lowers their gas price to $2.99 a gallon, and keeps it there for the three years.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler plans for Lancia to codevelop products, with some vehicles being shared.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Olivier Francois, Lancia's CEO, was appointed to the Chrysler division in October 2009.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Francois plans to reestablish the Chrysler brand as an upscale brand.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In October 2009, Dodge's car and truck lines were separated, with the name "Dodge" being used for cars, minivans, and crossovers and "Ram" for light- and medium-duty trucks and other commercial-use vehicles.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2011, Chrysler unveiled its "Imported From Detroit" campaign with ads featuring Detroit rapper Eminem, one of which aired during the Super Bowl.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The campaign highlighted the rejuvenation of the entire product lineup, which included the new, redesigned, and repackaged 2011 model year 200 sedans and 200 convertibles, the Chrysler 300 sedan, and the Chrysler Town & Country minivan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] As part of the campaign, Chrysler sold a line of clothing items featuring the Monument to Joe Louis, with proceeds being funneled to Detroit-area charities, including the Boys and Girls Clubs of Southeast Michigan, Habitat for Humanity Detroit and the Marshall Mathers Foundation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In March 2011, Chrysler Group LLC filed a lawsuit against Moda Group LLC (owner of Pure Detroit clothing retailer) for copying and selling merchandise with the "Imported from Detroit" slogan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler claimed it had notified defendant of its pending trademark application February 14, but the defendant argued Chrysler had not secured a trademark for the "Imported From Detroit" phrase.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] District Judge Arthur Tarnow ruled that Chrysler's request did not show that it would suffer irreparable harm or that it had a strong likelihood of winning its case.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Therefore, Pure Detroit's owner, Detroit retailer Moda Group LLC, can continue selling its "Imported from Detroit" products.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Tarnow also noted that Chrysler does not have a trademark on "Imported from Detroit" and rejected the automaker's argument that trademark law is not applicable to the case.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In March 2012, Chrysler Group LLC and Pure Detroit agreed to a March 27 mediation to try to settle the lawsuit over the clothing company's use of "Imported from Detroit" slogan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Pure Detroit stated that Chrysler has made false claims about the origins of three vehicles - Chrysler 200, Chrysler 300 and Chrysler Town & Country - none of which are built in Detroit.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Pure Detroit also said that Chrysler's Imported From Detroit merchandise is not being made in Detroit.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2012 Chrysler and Pure Detroit came to an undisclosed settlement.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler's Jefferson North Assembly, which makes the Jeep Grand Cherokee and Dodge Durango, is the only car manufacturing plant of any company remaining entirely in Detroit (General Motors operates a plant that is partly in Detroit and partly in Hamtramck).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2011, Eminem settled a lawsuit against Audi alleging the defendant had ripped off the Chrysler 300 Super Bowl commercial in the Audi A6 Avant ad.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Again in 2012, Chrysler advertised during the Super Bowl.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Its two-minute February 5, 2012 Super Bowl XLVI advertisement was titled "Halftime in America".
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The ad drew criticism from several leading U.S. conservatives, who suggested that its messaging implied that President Barack Obama deserved a second term and, as such, was political payback for Obama's support for the federal bailout of the company.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Asked about the criticism in a *60 Minutes* interview with Steve Kroft, Sergio Marchionne responded "just to rectify the record I paid back the loans at 19.7% Interest.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] I don't think I committed to do to a commercial on top of that" and characterized the Republican reaction as "unnecessary and out of place".
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] First introduced as MyGig, Chrysler Uconnect is a system that brings interactive ability to the in-car radio and telemetric-like controls to car settings.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] As of mid-2015, it was installed in hundreds of thousands of Fiat Chrysler vehicles.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] It connects to the Internet via the mobile network of AT&T, providing the car with its own IP address.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Internet connectivity using any Chrysler, Dodge, Jeep or Ram vehicle, via a Wi-Fi "hot-spot", is also available via Uconnect Web.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] According to Chrysler LLC, the hotspot range extends approximately 100 feet (30 m) from the vehicle in all directions, and combines both Wi-Fi and Sprint's 3G cellular connectivity.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Uconnect is available on several current and was available on several discontinued Chrysler models including the current Dodge Dart, Chrysler 300, Aspen, Sebring, Town and Country, Dodge Avenger, Caliber, Grand Caravan, Challenger, Charger, Journey, Nitro, and Ram.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In July 2015, IT security researchers announced a severe security flaw assumed to affect every Chrysler vehicle with Uconnect produced from late 2013 to early 2015.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] It allows hackers to gain access to the car over the Internet, and in the case of a Jeep Cherokee was demonstrated to enable an attacker to take control not just of the radio, A/C, and windshield wipers, but also of the car's steering, brakes and transmission.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler published a patch that car owners can download and install via a USB stick, or have a car dealer install for them.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Division that manufactured bearings and gears.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Division that built inboard, outboard engines, and various types of boats.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Desoto trucks were built and sold by Chrysler in Turkey until 1978, after which Askam took over the Turkish rights to the marque.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Name derived from the AMC Eagle model after Chrysler took over American Motors in 1987.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Replaced by Plymouth Trucks in the US in 1937 and folded into the Dodge Division after 1972 in Canada.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The Valiant was introduced in 1960 as a separate Chrysler brand, then was incorporated into the Plymouth line in the US starting in 1961.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1979, Chrysler, in cooperation with the United States Department of Energy, produced an experimental battery electric vehicle, the Chrysler ETV-1.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1992, Chrysler developed the Dodge EPIC concept minivan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 1993, Chrysler sold a limited-production electric minivan called the TEVan; only 56 were produced, mostly for electric utilities.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] A second generation, the EPIC (unrelated to the concept), was released in 1997 and discontinued in 1999.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler once owned the Global Electric Motorcars company, building low-speed neighborhood electric vehicles, but sold GEM to Polaris Industries in 2011.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In September 2007, Chrysler established ENVI, an in-house organization focused on electric-drive vehicles and related technologies which was disbanded by late 2009.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In August 2009, Chrysler took US$70 million in grants from the U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Department of Energy to develop a test fleet of 220 hybrid pickup trucks and minivans.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The first hybrid models, the Chrysler Aspen hybrid and the Dodge Durango hybrid, were discontinued a few months after production in 2008, sharing its GM-designed hybrid technology with GM, Daimler and BMW.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Chrysler was on the Advisory Council of the PHEV Research Center, and undertook a government sponsored demonstration project with Ram and minivan vehicles.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] In 2012, FCA CEO Sergio Marchionne stated that Chrysler and Fiat planned to focus primarily on alternative fuels, such as compressed natural gas and diesel, instead of hybrid and electric drivetrains for its consumer products.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Fiat Chrysler bought a total of 8.2 million megagrams of U.S. greenhouse gas emission credits from competitors including Toyota, Honda, Tesla and Nissan for the 2010, 2011, 2013, and 2014 model years.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] It had the worst fleet average fuel economy among major manufacturers selling in the US from model years 2012–2023.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] The dedicated tank building division of Chrysler, this division was founded as the Chrysler Tank division in 1940, originally with the intention of providing another production line for the M2 Medium Tank, so that the U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Army could more rapidly build up its inventory of the type.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] Its first plant was the Detroit Arsenal Tank Plant.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] After December 1941 and the United States' entry into the war against the Axis powers, the Tank division rapidly expanded, with new facilities such as the Tank Arsenal Proving Ground at (then) Utica, Michigan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p01] It also quickly widened the range of products it was developing and producing, including the M4 Sherman tank and the Chrysler A57 multibank tank engine.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] During World War II, essentially all of Chrysler's facilities were devoted to building military vehicles (the Jeep brand came later, after Chrysler acquired American Motors Corporation).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] They were also designing V12 and V16 hemi-engines producing 2,500 hp (1,864 kW; 2,535 PS) for airplanes, but they did not make it into production as jets were developed and were seen as the future for air travel.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] During the 1950s Cold War period, Chrysler made air raid sirens powered by its Hemi V-8 engines.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] When the Radiation Laboratory at MIT was established in 1941 to develop microwave radars, one of the first projects resulted in the SCR-584, the most widely recognized radar system of the war era.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] This system included a parabolic antenna six feet in diameter that was mechanically aimed in a helical pattern (round and round as well as up and down).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] One of Chrysler's most significant contributions to the war effort was in radar technology.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] For the final production design of this antenna and its highly complex drive mechanism, the Army's Signal Corps Laboratories turned to Chrysler's Central Engineering Office.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] There, the parabola was changed from aluminum to steel, allowing production to form using standard automotive presses.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] To keep weight down, 6,000 equally spaced holes were drilled in the face (this had no effect on the radiation pattern).
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] The drive mechanism was completely redesigned, using technology derived from Chrysler's research in automotive gears and differentials.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] The changes resulted in improved performance, reduced weight, and easier maintenance.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] A large portion of the Dodge plant was used in building 1,500 of the SCR-584 antennas as well as the vans used in the systems.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Army established the Ordnance Guided Missile Center (OGMC) at Redstone Arsenal, adjacent to Huntsville, Alabama.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] To form OGMC, over 1,000 civilian and military personnel were transferred from Fort Bliss, Texas.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Included was a group of German scientists and engineers led by Wernher von Braun; this group had been brought to America under Project Paperclip.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] OGMC designed the Army's first short-range ballistic missile, the PGM-11 Redstone, based on the WWII German V-2 missile.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Chrysler established the Missile Division to serve as the Redstone prime contractor, setting up an engineering operation in Huntsville and for production obtaining use from the U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Navy of a large plant in Sterling Heights, Michigan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] The Redstone was in active service from 1958 until 1964; it was also the first missile to test-launch a live nuclear weapon, first detonated in a 1958 test in the South Pacific.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Working together, the Missile Division and von Braun's team greatly increased the capability of the Redstone, resulting in the PGM-19 Jupiter, a medium-range ballistic missile.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] In May 1959, a Jupiter missile launched two small monkeys into space in a nose cone; this was America's first successful flight and recovery of live space payloads.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Responsibility for deploying Jupiter missiles was transferred from the Army to the Air Force; armed with nuclear warheads, they were first deployed in Italy and Turkey during the early 1960s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] In July 1959, NASA chose the Redstone missile as the basis for the Mercury-Redstone Launch Vehicle to be used for suborbital test flights of the Project Mercury spacecraft.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Three uncrewed MRLV launch attempts were made between November 1960 and March 1961, two of which were successful.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] The MRLV successfully launched the chimpanzee Ham, and astronauts Alan Shepard and Gus Grissom on three suborbital flights in January, May, and July 1961, respectively.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] America's more ambitious crewed space travel plans included the design of the Saturn series of heavy-lift launch vehicles by a team headed by Wernher von Braun.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Chrysler's Huntsville operation, then designated the Space Division, became Marshall Space Flight Center's prime contractor for the first stage of the Saturn I and Saturn IB versions.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] The design was based on a cluster of Redstone and Jupiter fuel tanks and Chrysler built it for the Apollo program in the Michoud Assembly Facility in East New Orleans, one of the largest manufacturing plants in the world.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] Between October 1961 and July 1975, NASA used ten Saturn Is and nine Saturn IBs for suborbital and orbital flights, all of which were successful; Chrysler missiles and boosters never suffered a launch failure.
[src:c-robert-kidder/chrysler-group-llc-p02] The division was also a subcontractor which modified one of the mobile launcher platforms for use with the Saturn IB rockets using Saturn V infrastructure.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus originated as several Native American settlements along the Scioto River.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The first European settlement was Franklinton, now a city neighborhood, in 1797.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus was founded in 1812 at the confluence of the Scioto and Olentangy rivers and was named after Italian explorer Christopher Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It was planned as the state capital due to its central location and officially became the capital in 1816.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city grew steadily through the 19th century as a transportation and industrial hub via the National Road, Ohio and Erie Canal, and several railroads.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Starting in the 1950s, Columbus experienced rapid suburban growth, becoming Ohio's largest city by area and population by the early 1990s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus diversified economically in the late 20th and early 21st centuries as a center for finance, insurance, education, and technology.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 2020s, the city became a major center for high technology, innovation, and advanced manufacturing, particularly in the fields of artificial intelligence, robotics, and semiconductor device fabrication.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Greater Columbus area is further home to the headquarters of *Fortune* 500 companies Cardinal Health, Nationwide, American Electric Power, Huntington Bancshares and Vertiv.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It hosts cultural institutions such as the Columbus Museum of Art, COSI, Franklin Park Conservatory and Ohio Theatre.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's major league professional sports teams include the Columbus Blue Jackets (NHL) and Columbus Crew (MLS).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city of Columbus was named after 15th-century Italian explorer Christopher Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It may be the largest city in the world named for the explorer (as the name of the Sri Lankan city of Colombo is of Sinhala origin), who sailed to and settled parts of the Americas on behalf of Isabella I of Castile and Spain.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Since the late 20th century, historians have criticized Columbus for initiating the European conquest of America and for abuse, enslavement, and subjugation of natives.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Efforts to remove symbols related to the explorer in the city date to the 1990s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Amid the George Floyd protests in 2020, several petitions pushed for the city to be renamed.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2021, the iconic 22-foot tall statue of Christopher Columbus was removed from the south side of City Hall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Nicknames for the city have included "the Discovery City", "Arch City", "Cap City", "Cowtown", "The Biggest Small Town in America" and "Cbus".
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Between 1000 B.C. and 1700 A.D., the Columbus metropolitan area was a center to indigenous cultures known as the Mound Builders, including the Adena, Hopewell and Fort Ancient peoples.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Remaining physical evidence of the cultures are their burial mounds and what they contained.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Most of Central Ohio's remaining mounds are located outside of Columbus city boundaries, though the Shrum Mound is maintained, now as part of a public park and historic site.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's Mound Street derives its name from a mound that existed by the intersection of Mound and High Streets.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The mound's clay was used in bricks for most of the city's initial brick buildings; many were subsequently used in the Ohio Statehouse.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's Ohio History Center maintains a collection of artifacts from these cultures.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The area including present-day Columbus once comprised the Ohio Country, under the nominal control of the French colonial empire through the Viceroyalty of New France from 1663 until 1763.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 18th century, European traders flocked to the area, attracted by the fur trade.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The area was often caught between warring factions, including American Indian and European interests.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 1740s, Pennsylvania traders overran the territory until the French forcibly evicted them.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Fighting for control of the territory in the French and Indian War became part of the Seven Years' War.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Up until the American Revolution, Central Ohio had continuously been the home of numerous indigenous villages.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] A Mingo village was located at the forks of the Scioto and Olentangy rivers, with Shawnee villages to the south and Wyandot and Delaware villages to the north.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Colonial militiamen burned down the Mingo village in 1774 during a raid.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] After the American Revolution, the Virginia Military District became part of the Ohio Country as a territory of Virginia.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Colonists from the East Coast moved in, but rather than finding an empty frontier, they encountered people of the Miami, Delaware, Wyandot, Shawnee and Mingo nations, as well as European traders.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The tribes resisted expansion by the fledgling United States, leading to years of bitter conflict.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The decisive Battle of Fallen Timbers resulted in the Treaty of Greenville in 1795, which finally opened the way for new settlements.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] By 1797, a young surveyor from Virginia named Lucas Sullivant had founded a permanent settlement on the west bank of the forks of the Scioto and Olentangy rivers.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] An admirer of Benjamin Franklin, Sullivant chose to name his frontier village "Franklinton".
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The location was desirable for its proximity to the navigable rivers – but Sullivant was initially foiled when, in 1798, a large flood wiped out the new settlement.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] He persevered, and the village was rebuilt, though somewhat more inland.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] After the Revolution, land comprising parts of Franklin and adjacent counties was set aside by Congress for settlement by Canadians and Nova Scotians who were sympathetic to the colonial cause and had their land and possessions seized by the British government.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Refugee Tract, consisting of 103,000 acres (42,000 ha), was 42 miles (68 km) long and 3–4.5 miles (4.8–7.2 km) wide, and was claimed by 67 eligible men.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Ohio Statehouse sits on land once contained in the Refugee Tract.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] After Ohio achieved statehood in 1803, political infighting among prominent Ohio leaders led to the state capital moving from Chillicothe to Zanesville and back again.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Desiring to settle on a location, the state legislature considered Franklinton, Dublin, Worthington and Delaware before compromising on a plan to build a new city in the state's center, near major transportation routes, primarily rivers.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Franklinton landowners had donated two 10-acre (4.0 ha) plots in an effort to convince the state to move its capital there.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The two spaces were set to become Capitol Square, including for the Ohio Statehouse and the Ohio Penitentiary.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Named in honor of Christopher Columbus, the city was founded on February 14, 1812, on the "High Banks opposite Franklinton at the Forks of the Scioto most known as Wolf's Ridge." At the time, this area was a dense forestland, used only as a hunting ground.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city was incorporated as a borough on February 10, 1816.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Pike served as the first appointed mayor.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Although the recent War of 1812 had brought prosperity to the area, the subsequent recession and conflicting claims to the land threatened the new town's success.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Early conditions were abysmal, with frequent bouts of fevers, attributed to malaria from the flooding rivers, and an outbreak of cholera in 1833.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It led Columbus to create the Board of Health, now part of the Columbus Public Health department.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The outbreak, which remained in the city from July to September 1833, killed 100 people.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus was without direct river or trail connections to other Ohio cities, leading to slow initial growth.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The National Road reached Columbus from Baltimore in 1831, which complemented the city's new link to the Ohio and Erie Canal, both of which facilitated a population boom.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] A wave of European immigrants led to the creation of two ethnic enclaves on the city's outskirts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] A large Irish population settled in the north along Naghten Street (presently Nationwide Boulevard), while the Germans took advantage of the cheap land to the south, creating a community that came to be known as the *Das Alte Südende* (The Old South End).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus's German population constructed numerous breweries, Trinity Lutheran Seminary and Capital University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] With a population of 3,500, Columbus was officially chartered as a city on March 3, 1834.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] On that day, the legislature carried out a special act, which granted legislative authority to the city council and judicial authority to the mayor.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Elections were held in April of that year, with voters choosing John Brooks as the first popularly elected mayor.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus annexed the then-separate city of Franklinton in 1837.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1850, the Columbus and Xenia Railroad became the first railroad into the city, followed by the Cleveland, Columbus and Cincinnati Railroad in 1851.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The two railroads built a joint Union Station on the east side of High Street just north of Naghten (then called North Public Lane).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Rail traffic into Columbus increased: by 1875, eight railroads served Columbus, and the rail companies built a new, more elaborate station.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Another cholera outbreak hit Columbus in 1849, prompting the opening of the city's Green Lawn Cemetery.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] On January 7, 1857, the Ohio Statehouse finally opened after 18 years of construction.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Before the abolition of slavery in the Southern United States in 1863, the Underground Railroad was active in Columbus and was led, in part, by James Preston Poindexter.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Poindexter arrived in Columbus in the 1830s and became a Baptist preacher and leader in the city's African-American community until the turn of the century.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] During the Civil War, Columbus was a major base for the volunteer Union Army.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It housed 26,000 troops and held up to 9,000 Confederate prisoners of war at Camp Chase, at what is now the Hilltop neighborhood of west Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Over 2,000 Confederate soldiers remain buried at the site, making it one of the North's largest Confederate cemeteries.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] By virtue of the Morrill Act of 1862, the Ohio Agricultural and Mechanical College – which eventually became the Ohio State University – was founded in 1870 on the former estate of William and Hannah Neil.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] By the end of the 19th century, Columbus was home to several major manufacturing businesses.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Jeffrey Manufacturing Company was a major supplier of coal mining equipment.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city became known as the "Buggy Capital of the World", thanks to the two dozen buggy factories, notably the Columbus Buggy Company, founded in 1875 by C.D.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Columbus Consolidated Brewing Company also rose to prominence during this time and might have achieved even greater success were it not for the Anti-Saloon League in neighboring Westerville.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Bush presided over the Buckeye Steel Castings Company.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus was also a popular location for labor organizations.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1886, Samuel Gompers founded the American Federation of Labor in Druid's Hall on South Fourth Street, and in 1890, the United Mine Workers of America was founded at the old City Hall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Columbus Experiment was an environmental project in 1908 which involved construction of the first water plant in the world to apply filtration and softening, designed and invented by two brothers, Clarence and Charles Hoover.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Those working to construct the project included Jeremiah O'Shaughnessy, name-bearer of the Columbus metropolitan area's O'Shaughnessy Dam.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] This invention helped drastically reduce typhoid deaths.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The essential design is still used today.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The 1910 Columbus streetcar strike took place in downtown Columbus; the strike action turned into a violent riot, though was eventually unsuccessful.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus earned one of its nicknames, "The Arch City", because of the dozens of wooden arches that spanned High Street at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The arches illuminated the thoroughfare and eventually became the means by which electric power was provided to the new streetcars.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city tore down the arches and replaced them with cluster lights in 1914 but reconstructed them from metal in the Short North neighborhood in 2002 for their unique historical interest.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] On March 25, 1913, the Great Flood of 1913 devastated the neighborhood of Franklinton, leaving over 90 people dead and thousands of West Side residents homeless.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] To prevent flooding, the Army Corps of Engineers recommended widening the Scioto River through downtown, constructing new bridges and building a retaining wall along its banks.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] With the strength of the post-World War I economy, a construction boom occurred in the 1920s, resulting in a new civic center, the Ohio Theatre, the American Insurance Union Citadel and to the north, a massive new Ohio Stadium.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Although the American Professional Football Association was founded in Canton in 1920, its head offices moved to Columbus in 1921 to the New Hayden Building and remained in the city until 1941.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1922, the association's name was changed to the National Football League.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Nearly a decade later, in 1931, at a convention in the city, the Jehovah's Witnesses took that name by which they are known today.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The effects of the Great Depression were less severe in Columbus, as the city's diversified economy helped it fare better than its Rust Belt neighbors.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] World War II brought many new jobs and another population surge.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] This time, most new arrivals were migrants from the "extraordinarily depressed rural areas" of Appalachia, who would soon account for more than a third of Columbus's growing population.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1948, the Town and Country Shopping Center opened in suburban Whitehall, and it is now regarded as one of the first modern shopping centers in the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The construction of the Interstate Highway System signaled the arrival of rapid suburb development in central Ohio.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] To protect the city's tax base from this suburbanization, Columbus adopted a policy of linking sewer and water hookups to annexation to the city.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] By the early 1990s, Columbus had grown to become Ohio's largest city in land area and in population.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Efforts to revitalize downtown Columbus have had some success in recent decades, though like most major American cities, some architectural heritage was lost in the process.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 1970s, landmarks such as Union Station and the Neil House hotel were razed to construct high-rise offices and big retail space.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The PNC Bank building was constructed in 1977, as well as the Nationwide Plaza buildings and other towers that sprouted during this period.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The construction of the Greater Columbus Convention Center has brought major conventions and trade shows to the city.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] AmeriFlora '92 was held in the city in 1992, part of the Christopher Columbus Quincentennial Jubilee, celebrating the 500th anniversary of Columbus's first voyage.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The organizers also planned to create a replica Native American village, among other attractions.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Local and national native leaders protested the event with a day of mourning, followed by protests and fasts at City Hall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The protests prevented the native village from being exhibited.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] A protest also took place during the dedication of the *Santa Maria* replica, an event held in late 1991 on the day before Columbus Day and in time for the jubilee.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1999, just before the turn of the 21st century, the city's first African American mayor was elected.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Michael Coleman, a Democrat, served 16 years, the longest of any mayor of the city.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Coleman's administration led to Nationwide Insurance redeveloping the former Ohio Penitentiary site and nearby blocks into the Arena District.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Similar new construction and redevelopment was taking place in the Brewery District, and a flood wall was completed in Franklinton in 2004, finally letting development resume in the neighborhood.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Scioto Mile began development along the riverfront, an area that already had the Miranova Corporate Center and The Condominiums at North Bank Park.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The 2010 United States foreclosure crisis forced the city to purchase numerous foreclosed, vacant properties to renovate or demolish them at a cost of tens of millions of dollars.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city is focused on downtown revitalization, with recent projects being the Columbus Commons park, parks along the Scioto Mile developed along with a reshaped riverfront, and developments in the Arena District and Franklinton.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic in Columbus began when the city reported its first official cases of COVID-19 in February and March 2020 and declared a state of emergency.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Later in 2020, protests over the murder of George Floyd occurred in the city from May 28 into August.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In November 2024, about a dozen masked men dressed in black carried red swastika flags in Columbus chanting racial slurs and using pepper spray.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In July 2024, Columbus was subject to a ransomware attack, for which the hacker group Rhysidia took credit.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In August 2024, Columbus Mayor Andrew Ginther claimed that the files obtained by Rhysidia were "unusable" to the thieves due to being either encrypted or corrupted.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Ginther's assertion was subsequently shown to be false by security researcher David Leroy Ross, who revealed that the files were intact and contained data including names from domestic violence cases and Social Security numbers of crime victims.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus then sued Ross for alleged criminal acts, negligence, and civil conversion, as well as taking out a restraining order against Ross, both of which actions were later defended by City Attorney Zach Klein.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In response, a number of prominent cybersecurity researchers called on the city to drop the lawsuit.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In the 2020s, the city became a center for high technology, innovation, and high-tech manufacturing, particularly in artificial intelligence, robotics, and semiconductor device fabrication.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2023, Intel announced plans to construct a $20 billion factory and Honda expanding its presence along with LG Energy Solutions with a $4.4 billion battery manufactory facility in Fayette County.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In January 2025, Anduril announced a series of Arsenal Projects, hyperscaling computer facilities for autonomous weapons.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] They also announced the construction of a manufacturing facility in Columbus, to be named "Arsenal-1", with subsequent Arsenals planned.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] This facility will be designed to be able to manufacture advanced systems faster than near peer manufacturers.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It is noted for its close ties with Ohio State University, with Anduril Industries sponsoring the football program for the 2025 to 2026 year, connections to the college administration, and much of Anduril-1's employees hailing from its applied science programs.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The confluence of the Scioto and Olentangy rivers is just northwest of Downtown Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Several smaller tributaries course through the Columbus metropolitan area, including Alum Creek, Big Walnut Creek and Darby Creek.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is considered to have relatively flat topography thanks to a large glacier that covered most of Ohio during the Wisconsin Ice Age.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] However, there are sizable differences in elevation through the area, with the high point of Franklin County being 1,132 feet (345 meters) above sea level near New Albany, and the low point being 670 ft (200 m) where the Scioto River leaves the county near Lockbourne.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Several ravines near the rivers and creeks also add variety to the landscape.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Tributaries to Alum Creek and the Olentangy River cut through shale, while tributaries to the Scioto River cut through limestone.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The numerous rivers and streams beside low-lying areas in Central Ohio contribute to a history of flooding in the region; the most significant was the Great Flood of 1913 in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city has a total area of 223.11 square miles (577.9 square kilometers), of which 217.17 sq mi (562.5 km2) is land and 5.94 sq mi (15.4 km2) is water.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has the largest land area of any Ohio city; this is due to Jim Rhodes's tactic to annex suburbs while serving as mayor.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] As surrounding communities grew or were constructed, they came to require access to waterlines, which was under the sole control of the municipal water system.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Rhodes told these communities that if they wanted water, they would have to submit to assimilation into Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has a wide diversity of neighborhoods with different characters, and is thus sometimes known as a "city of neighborhoods".
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Some of the most prominent neighborhoods include the Arena District, the Brewery District, Clintonville, Franklinton, German Village, The Short North and Victorian Village.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's climate is humid continental (Köppen climate classification *Dfa*) transitional with the humid subtropical (Köppen climate classification *Cfa*) to the south characterized by warm, muggy summers and cold, dry winters.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is within USDA hardiness zone 6b, bordering on 7a.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Winter snowfall is relatively light, since the city is not in the typical path of strong winter lows, such as the Nor'easters that strike cities farther east.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It is also too far south and west for lake-effect snow from Lake Erie to have much effect, although the lakes to the north contribute to long stretches of cloudy spells in winter.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The highest temperature recorded in Columbus is 106 °F (41 °C), which occurred twice during the Dust Bowl of the 1930s: once on July 21, 1934, and again on July 14, 1936.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The lowest recorded temperature was −22 °F (−30 °C), occurring on January 19, 1994.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is subject to severe weather typical to the Midwestern United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Severe thunderstorms can bring lightning, large hail and on rare occasions tornadoes, especially during the spring and sometimes through fall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] A tornado that occurred on October 11, 2006, caused F2 damage.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Floods, blizzards and ice storms can also occur from time to time.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has focused on reducing its environmental impact and carbon footprint.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2020, a citywide ballot measure was approved, giving Columbus an electricity aggregation plan which will supply it with 100% renewable energy by the start of 2023.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Its vendor, AEP Energy, plans to construct new wind and solar farms in Ohio to help supply the electricity.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The largest sources of pollution in the county, as of 2019, are Ohio State University's McCracken Power Plant, the landfill operated by the Solid Waste Authority of Central Ohio (SWACO) and the Anheuser-Busch Columbus Brewery.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Anheuser-Busch has a company-wide goal of reducing emissions by 25% by 2025.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Ohio State plans to construct a new heat and power plant, also powered by fossil fuels, but set to reduce emissions by about 30%.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] SWACO manages to capture 75% of its methane emissions to use in producing energy, and is looking to reduce emissions further.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] As of the 2020 census, Columbus had a population of 905,748.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] 21.9% of residents were under the age of 18 and 11.0% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] For every 100 females there were 95.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 93.2 males age 18 and over.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] 99.9% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] There were 382,038 households in Columbus, of which 26.5% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Of all households, 31.4% were married-couple households, 25.2% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 34.1% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] About 35.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] There were 415,456 housing units, of which 8.0% were vacant.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 8.2%.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus historically had a significant population of white people.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 1900, whites made up 93.4% of the population.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Although European immigration has declined, the Columbus metropolitan area has recently experienced increases in African, Asian and Latin American immigration, including groups from Mexico, India, Nepal, Bhutan, Somalia and China.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] While the Asian population is diverse, the city's Hispanic community is mainly made up of Mexican Americans, although there is a notable Puerto Rican population.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Many other countries of origin are represented in lesser numbers, largely due to the international draw of Ohio State University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] 2008 estimates indicate that roughly 116,000 of the city's residents are foreign-born, accounting for 82% of the new residents between 2000 and 2006 at a rate of 105 per week.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] 40% of the immigrants came from Asia, 23% from Africa, 22% from Latin America and 13% from Europe.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city had the second-largest Somali and Somali American population in the country, as of 2004, as well as the largest expatriate Bhutanese-Nepali population in the world, as of 2018.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Due to its demographics, which include a mix of races and a wide range of incomes, as well as urban, suburban and nearby rural areas, Columbus is considered a "typical" American city, leading retail and restaurant chains to use it as a test market for new products.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] For similar reasons, the city was chosen as the launch city for the QUBE cable television service.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has maintained a steady population growth since its establishment.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Its slowest growth, from 1850 to 1860, is primarily attributed to the city's cholera epidemic in the 1850s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] According to the 2017 Japanese Direct Investment Survey by the Consulate-General of Japan, Detroit, 838 Japanese nationals lived in Columbus, making it the municipality with the state's second-largest Japanese national population, after Dublin.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is home to a proportional LGBT community, with an estimated 34,952 gay, lesbian or bisexual residents.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The 2018 American Community Survey (ACS) reported an estimated 366,034 households, 32,276 of which were held by unmarried partners.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] 1,395 of these were female householder and female-partner households, and 1,456 were male householder and male-partner households.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has been rated as one of the best cities in the country for gays and lesbians to live, and also as the most underrated gay city in the country.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Stonewall Columbus formed in 1981 after a group of protestors organized a march against a proposed office of Moral Majority, a political organization lead by pastor Jerry Falwell, Sr.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The next year, Stonewall hosted its first Pride Parade.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In July 2012, three years prior to legal same-sex marriage in the United States, the Columbus City Council unanimously passed a domestic partnership registry.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has numerous Italian Americans, with groups including the Columbus Italian Club, Columbus Piave Club and the Abruzzi Club.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Italian Village, a neighborhood near Downtown Columbus, has had a prominent Italian American community since the 1890s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The community has helped promote the influence Christopher Columbus had in drawing European attention to the Americas.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Italian explorer, erroneously credited with the lands' discovery, has been posthumously criticized by historians for initiating colonization and for abuse, enslavement and subjugation of natives.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In addition to the city being named for the explorer, its seal and flag depict a ship he used for his first voyage to the Americas, the *Santa María*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] A similar-size replica of the ship, the Santa Maria Ship & Museum, was displayed downtown from 1991 to 2014.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city's Discovery District and Discovery Bridge are named in reference to Columbus's "discovery" of the Americas; the bridge includes artistic bronze medallions featuring symbols of the explorer.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Genoa Park, downtown, is named after Genoa, the birthplace of Christopher Columbus and one of Columbus's sister cities.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Christopher Columbus Quincentennial Jubilee, celebrating the 500th anniversary of Columbus's first voyage, was held in the city in 1992.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Its organizers spent $95 million on it, creating the horticultural exhibition AmeriFlora '92.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The protests prevented the native village from being exhibited, and annual fasts continued until 1997.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city has three outdoor statues of the explorer; the statue at City Hall was acquired, delivered and dedicated with the assistance of the Italian American community.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Protests in 2017 aimed for this statue to be removed, followed by the city in 2018 ceasing to recognize Columbus Day as a city holiday.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] During the 2020 George Floyd protests, petitions were created to remove all three statues and rename the city of Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city was one of eight cities to be offered the 360 ft (110 m) *Birth of the New World* statue, in 1993.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The statue, also of Christopher Columbus, was completed in Puerto Rico in 2016 and is the tallest in the United States – 45 ft (14 m) taller than the Statue of Liberty, including its pedestal.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] At least six U.S. cities, including Columbus, rejected it based on its height and design.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] According to the 2019 American Values Atlas, 26% of Columbus metropolitan area residents are unaffiliated with a religious tradition.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] 17% of area residents identify as White evangelical Protestants, 14% as White mainline Protestants, 11% as Black Protestants, 11% as White Catholics, 5% as Hispanic Catholics, 3% as other nonwhite Catholics, 2% as other nonwhite Protestants and 2% as Mormons.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Hindus, Buddhists, Jews and Latino Protestants each made up 1% of the population, while Jehovah's Witnesses, Orthodox Christians, Muslims, Unitarians, and members of New Age or other religions each made up under 0.5% of the population.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has a generally strong and diverse economy based on education, insurance, banking, fashion, defense, aviation, food, logistics, steel, energy, medical research, health care, hospitality, retail and technology.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2010, it was one of the 10 best big cities in the country, according to Relocate America, a real estate research firm.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] According to the Federal Reserve Bank of St.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Louis, the GDP of Columbus in 2019 was $134 billion (~$162 billion in 2024).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] During the Great Recession between 2007 and 2009, Columbus's economy was not impacted as much as the rest of the country, due to decades of diversification work by long-time corporate residents, business leaders and political leaders.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The administration of former mayor Michael B.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Coleman continued this work, although the city faced financial turmoil and had to increase taxes, allegedly due in part to fiscal mismanagement.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Because Columbus is the state capital, there is a large government presence in the city.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Including city, county, state and federal employers, government jobs provide the largest single source of employment within Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2019, the city had six corporations named to the U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Fortune 500 list: Alliance Data, Nationwide Mutual Insurance Company, American Electric Power, L Brands, Huntington Bancshares and Cardinal Health in suburban Dublin.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Fast-food chains Wendy's and White Castle are also headquartered in the Columbus area.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Major foreign corporations operating or with divisions in the city include Germany-based Siemens and Roxane Laboratories, Finland-based Vaisala, Tomasco Mulciber Inc., A Y Manufacturing, as well as Switzerland-based ABB and Mettler Toledo.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city also has a significant fashion and retail presence, home to companies such as Big Lots, L Brands, Abercrombie & Fitch, DSW and Express.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] North Market, a public market and food hall, is located downtown near the Short North.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It is the only remaining public market of Columbus's original four marketplaces.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus-style pizza features a thin crust and a slightly sweet tomato sauce.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The cheese, usually mozzarella or provolone, fully covers the crust without leaving any bare areas.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The pizza is round but is cut into squares.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Numerous restaurant chains are based in the Columbus area, including Charleys Philly Steaks, Bibibop Asian Grill, Steak Escape, White Castle, Cameron Mitchell Restaurants, Bob Evans Restaurants, Max & Erma's, Damon's Grill, Donatos Pizza and Wendy's.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Wendy's, the world's third-largest hamburger fast-food chain, operated its first store downtown as both a museum and a restaurant until March 2007, when the establishment was closed due to low revenue.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The company is presently headquartered outside the city in nearby Dublin.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Budweiser has a major brewery located on the north side, just south of I-270 and Worthington.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is also home to many local micro breweries and pubs.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Asian frozen food manufacturer Kahiki Foods was located on the east side of Columbus, created during the operation of the Kahiki Supper Club restaurant in Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The food company now operates in the suburb of Gahanna and has been owned by the South Korean-based company CJ CheilJedang since 2018.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Wasserstrom Company, a major supplier of equipment and supplies for restaurants, is located on the north side.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has over 170 notable buildings listed on the National Register of Historic Places; it also maintains its own register, the Columbus Register of Historic Properties, with 82 entries.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city also maintains four historic districts not listed on its register: German Village, Italian Village, Victorian Village, and the Brewery District.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Construction of the Ohio Statehouse began in 1839 on a 10-acre (4 ha) plot of land donated by four prominent Columbus landowners.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] This plot formed Capitol Square, which was not part of the city's original layout.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Built of Columbus limestone from the Marble Cliff Quarry Co., the Statehouse stands on foundations 18 feet (5.5 m) deep that were laid by prison labor gangs rumored to have been composed largely of masons jailed for minor infractions.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It features several artworks within and outside the building, including the *William McKinley Monument* dedicated in 1907.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Within the Driving Park heritage district lies the original home of Eddie Rickenbacker, a World War I fighter pilot ace.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Built in 1895, the house was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Preservationists and the public have sometimes run into conflict with developers hoping to revitalize an area and demolish certain buildings, and historically with the city and state government, which led programs of urban renewal in the 20th century.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has a wide variety of museums and galleries.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Its primary art museum is the Columbus Museum of Art, which operates its main location as well as the Pizzuti Collection, featuring contemporary art.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The museum, founded in 1878, focuses on European and American art up to early modernism that includes extraordinary examples of Impressionism, German Expressionism and Cubism.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Another prominent art museum in the city is the Wexner Center for the Arts, a contemporary art gallery and research facility operated by the Ohio State University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Ohio History Connection is headquartered in Columbus, with its flagship museum, the 250,000-square-foot (23,000 m2) Ohio History Center, 4 mi (6.4 km) north of downtown.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Adjacent to the museum is Ohio Village, a replica of a village around the time of the American Civil War.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Columbus Historical Society also features historical exhibits, which focus more closely on life in Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] COSI is a large science and children's museum in downtown Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The present building, the former Central High School, was completed in November 1999, opposite downtown on the west bank of the Scioto River.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In 2009, *Parents* magazine named COSI one of the 10 best science centers for families in the country.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Other science museums include the Orton Geological Museum and the Museum of Biological Diversity, which are both part of Ohio State University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Franklin Park Conservatory is the city's botanical garden, which opened in 1895.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] It features over 400 species of plants in a large Victorian-style glass greenhouse building that includes rain forest, desert and Himalayan mountain biomes.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The National Veterans Memorial and Museum, which opened in 2018, focuses on the personal stories of military veterans throughout U.S. history.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The museum replaced the Franklin County Veterans Memorial, which opened in 1955.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Other notable museums in the city include the Central Ohio Fire Museum, Billy Ireland Cartoon Library & Museum and the Ohio Craft Museum.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus is the home of many performing arts institutions including the Columbus Symphony Orchestra, Opera Columbus, BalletMet Columbus, the ProMusica Chamber Orchestra, The Contemporary Theatre of Ohio, Columbus Children's Theatre, Shadowbox Live, and the Columbus Jazz Orchestra.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Throughout the summer, the Actors' Theatre of Columbus offers free performances of Shakespearean plays in an open-air amphitheater in Schiller Park in historic German Village.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Columbus Youth Ballet Academy was founded in the 1980s by ballerina and artistic director Shir Lee Wu, a discovery of Martha Graham.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Wu was the long-time artistic director of the Columbus City Ballet School and taught classes there until her death in 2021.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Columbus has several large concert venues, including the Nationwide Arena, Value City Arena, Express Live!, Mershon Auditorium and the Newport Music Hall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] In May 2009, the Lincoln Theatre, formerly a center for Black culture in Columbus, reopened after an extensive restoration.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Not far from the Lincoln Theatre is the King Arts Complex, which hosts a variety of cultural events.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The city also has several theaters downtown, including the historic Palace Theatre, the Ohio Theatre and the Southern Theatre.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] Broadway Across America often presents touring Broadway musicals in these larger venues.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The Vern Riffe Center for Government and the Arts houses the Capitol Theatre and three smaller studio theaters, providing a home for resident performing arts companies.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p01] The 2018 film *Ready Player One* is set in Columbus, though not filmed in the city.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus hosts two major league professional sports teams: the Columbus Blue Jackets of the National Hockey League (NHL), which play at Nationwide Arena, and the Columbus Crew of Major League Soccer (MLS), which play at ScottsMiracle-Gro Field.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Crew previously played at Historic Crew Stadium, the first soccer-specific stadium built in the United States for a Major League Soccer team.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Crew were one of the original members of MLS and won their first MLS Cup in 2008, a second title in 2020, and a third title in 2023.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Crew moved into then named Lower.com Field in the summer of 2021, which will also feature a mixed-use development site named Confluence Village.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] ScottsMiracle-Gro Field will host a total of nine Olympic soccer matches during the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Clippers, the International League affiliate of the Cleveland Guardians, play in Huntington Park, which opened in 2009.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city was home to the Panhandles/Tigers football team from 1901 to 1926; they are credited with playing in the first NFL game against another NFL opponent.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In the late 1990s, the Columbus Quest won the only two championships during American Basketball League's two-and-a-half season existence.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Ohio Aviators were based in Obetz, Ohio, and began play in the only PRO Rugby season before the league folded.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] From 1883 to 1884, Columbus was the home of the Columbus Buckeyes of Major League Baseball, who played two seasons in the American Association before folding operations after the 1884 season.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Since 2023, Columbus has been home to the Columbus Fury women's professional volleyball team, one of seven teams to launch with the Pro Volleyball Federation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The team plays home games at Nationwide Arena.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus NWSL team will begin play in 2028.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is home to one of the nation's most competitive intercollegiate programs, the Ohio State Buckeyes of Ohio State University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The program has placed in the top 10 final standings of the Director's Cup five times since 2000–2001, including No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The university funds 36 varsity teams, consisting of 17 male, 16 female and three co-educational teams.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2007–2008 and 2008–2009, the program generated the second-most revenue for college programs behind the Texas Longhorns of The University of Texas at Austin.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Ohio State Buckeyes are a member of the NCAA's Big Ten Conference, and their football team plays home games at Ohio Stadium.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Ohio State–Michigan football game (known colloquially as "The Game") is the final game of the regular season and is played in November each year, alternating between Columbus and Ann Arbor, Michigan.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2000, ESPN ranked the Ohio State–Michigan game as the greatest rivalry in North American sports.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Moreover, "Buckeye fever" permeates Columbus culture year-round and forms a major part of Columbus's cultural identity.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] During the winter months, the Buckeyes basketball and hockey teams are also major sporting attractions.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus has a long history in motorsports, hosting the world's first 24-hour car race at the Columbus Driving Park in 1905, which was organized by the Columbus Auto Club.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Motor Speedway was built in 1945 and held its first motorcycle race in 1946.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2010, the Ohio State University student-built Buckeye Bullet 2, a fuel-cell vehicle, set an FIA world speed record for electric vehicles in reaching 303.025 mph, eclipsing the previous record of 302.877 mph.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The annual All American Quarter Horse Congress, the world's largest single-breed horse show, attracts approximately 500,000 visitors to the Ohio Expo Center each October.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus hosts the annual Arnold Sports Festival.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Hosted by Arnold Schwarzenegger, the event has grown to eight Olympic sports and 22,000 athletes competing in 80 events.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Westside Barbell, a world-renowned powerlifting gym, is located in Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Its founder, Louie Simmons, is known for his popularization of the "Conjugate Method", while he is also credited with inventing training machines for reverse hyper-extensions and belt squats.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Westside Barbell is known for producing multiple world record holders in powerlifting.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Bullies were two-time champions of the American Football League (1940–1941).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Ohio Roller Derby (formerly Ohio Roller Girls) was founded in Columbus in 2005 and still competes internationally in Women's Flat Track Derby Association play.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The team is regularly ranked in the top 60 internationally.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus's Recreation and Parks Department oversees about 370 city parks.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Also in the area are 19 regional parks and the Metro Parks, which are part of the Columbus and Franklin County Metropolitan Park District.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] These parks include Clintonville's Whetstone Park and the Columbus Park of Roses, a 13-acre (5.3 ha) rose garden.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Chadwick Arboretum on Ohio State's campus features a large and varied collection of plants, while its Olentangy River Wetland Research Park is an experimental wetland open to the public.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Downtown, the painting *A Sunday Afternoon on the Island of La Grande Jatte* is represented in topiary at Columbus's Topiary Park.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Also near downtown, the Scioto Audubon Metro Park on the Whittier Peninsula opened in 2009 and includes a large Audubon nature center focused on the birdwatching the area is known for.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Zoo and Aquarium's collections include lowland gorillas, polar bears, manatees, Siberian tigers, cheetahs and kangaroos.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Also in the zoo complex is the Zoombezi Bay water park and amusement park.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Annual festivities in Columbus include the Ohio State Fair – one of the largest state fairs in the country – as well as the Columbus Arts Festival and the Jazz & Rib Fest, both of which occur on the downtown riverfront.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In mid-May from 2007 to 2018, Columbus was home to Rock on the Range, which was held at Historic Crew Stadium and marketed as America's biggest rock festival.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The festival, which took place on a Friday, Saturday and Sunday, has hosted Metallica, Red Hot Chili Peppers, Slipknot and other notable bands.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In May 2019, it was officially replaced by the Sonic Temple Art & Music Festival.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] During the first weekend in June, the bars of Columbus's North Market District host the Park Street Festival, which attracts thousands of visitors to a massive party in bars and on the street.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] June's second-to-last weekend sees one of the Midwest's largest gay pride parades, Columbus Pride, reflecting the city's sizable gay population.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city's largest dining event, Restaurant Week Columbus, is held twice a year in mid-January and mid-July.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2010, more than 40,000 diners went to 40 participating restaurants, and $5,000 (~$7,382 in 2025) was donated the Mid-Ohio Foodbank on behalf of sponsors and participating restaurants.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Around the Fourth of July, Columbus hosts Red, White, and Boom! on the Scioto riverfront downtown, attracting crowds of over 500,000 people and featuring the largest fireworks display in the Midwest.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The namesake of similar celebrations nationwide, the first originated in Columbus in 1981.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Short North is host to the monthly Gallery Hop, which attracts hundreds to the neighborhood's art galleries (which all open their doors to the public until late at night) and street musicians.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Hilltop Bean Dinner is an annual event held on Columbus's West Side that celebrates the city's Civil War heritage near the historic Camp Chase Cemetery.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] At the end of September, German Village throws an annual Oktoberfest celebration that features German food, beer, music and crafts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus also hosts many conventions in the Greater Columbus Convention Center, a large convention center on the north edge of downtown.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Completed in 1993, the 1.8-million-square-foot (170,000 m2) convention center was designed by architect Peter Eisenman, who also designed the Wexner Center.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Both of the metropolitan area's major shopping centers are located in Columbus: Easton Town Center and Polaris Fashion Place.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Jacobs built the area's first three major shopping malls in the 1960s: Westland, Northland and Eastland.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Near Northland Mall was The Continent, an open-air mall in the Northland area, mostly vacant and pending redevelopment.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus City Center was built downtown in 1988, alongside the first location of Lazarus; this mall closed in 2009 and was demolished in 2011.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Easton Town Center was built in 1999 and Polaris Fashion Place in 2001.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city is administered by a mayor and a nine-member unicameral Columbus City Council elected in two classes every two years to four-year terms at large.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is the largest city in the United States that elects its city council at large as opposed to districts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The mayor appoints the director of safety and the director of public service.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The people elect the auditor, municipal court clerk, municipal court judges and city attorney.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] A charter commission, elected in 1913, submitted a new charter in May 1914, offering a modified federal form, with a number of progressive features, such as nonpartisan ballot, preferential voting, recall of elected officials, the referendum and a small council elected at large.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The charter was adopted, effective January 1, 1916.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Andrew Ginther has been the mayor of Columbus since 2016.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] As Ohio's capital and the county seat, Columbus hosts numerous federal, state, county and city government offices and courts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Courthouse, one of several courts for the District Court for the Southern District of Ohio, after moving from 121 E.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Bricker Federal Building, has offices for U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Senator Sherrod Brown, as well as for the Internal Revenue Service, the Social Security Administration and the Departments of Housing & Urban Development and Agriculture.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The State of Ohio's capitol building, the Ohio Statehouse, is located in the center of downtown on Capitol Square.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] It houses the Ohio House of Representatives and Ohio Senate.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] It also contains the ceremonial offices of the governor, lieutenant governor, state treasurer and state auditor.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Supreme Court, Court of Claims and Judicial Conference are located in the Thomas J.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Moyer Ohio Judicial Center downtown by the Scioto River.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The building, built in 1933 to house 10 state agencies along with the State Library of Ohio, became the Supreme Court after extensive renovations from 2001 to 2004.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Franklin County operates the Franklin County Government Center, a complex at the southern end of downtown Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The center includes the county's municipal court, common pleas court, correctional center, juvenile detention center and sheriff's office.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Coleman Government Center holds offices for the departments of building and zoning services, public service, development and public utilities.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Also nearby is 77 North Front Street, which holds Columbus's city attorney office, income-tax division, public safety, human resources, civil service and purchasing departments.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The structure, built in 1929, was the police headquarters until 1991, and was then dormant until it was given a $34 million renovation from 2011 to 2013.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Municipal police duties are performed by the Columbus Division of Police, while emergency medical services (EMS) and fire protection are through the Columbus Division of Fire.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Ohio Homeland Security operates the Strategic Analysis and Information Center (SAIC) fusion center in Columbus's Hilltop neighborhood.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The facility is the state's primary public intelligence hub and one of the few in the country that uses state, local, federal and private resources.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus has a history of governmental and nonprofit support for low-income residents and the homeless.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Nevertheless, the homelessness rate has steadily risen since at least 2007.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Poverty and differences in quality of life have grown, as well; Columbus was noted as the second-most economically segregated large metropolitan area in 2015, in a study by the University of Toronto.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] It also ranked 45th of the 50 largest metropolitan areas in terms of social mobility, according to a 2015 Harvard University study.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is the home of two public colleges: the Ohio State University, one of the largest college campuses in the United States, and Columbus State Community College.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2009, Ohio State University was ranked No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] News & World Report* on its list of best public universities, and No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] 56 overall, scoring in the first tier of schools nationally.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Some of Ohio State's graduate school programs placed in the top 5, including No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] 5 for both best veterinary programs and best pharmacy programs.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The specialty graduate programs of social psychology was ranked No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] 2, and elementary education, secondary teacher education, administration/supervision was No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Three major suburban schools also have an influence on Columbus's educational landscape: Bexley's Capital University, Westerville's Otterbein University and Delaware's Ohio Wesleyan University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus City Schools (CCS) is the largest district in Ohio, with 55,000 pupils.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] CCS operates 142 elementary, middle and high schools, including a number of magnet schools (which are referred to as alternative schools within the school system).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The suburbs operate their own districts, typically serving students in one or more townships, with districts sometimes crossing municipal boundaries.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Roman Catholic Diocese of Columbus also operates several parochial elementary and high schools.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The area's second-largest school district is South-Western City Schools, which encompasses southwestern Franklin County, including a slice of Columbus itself.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Other portions of Columbus are zoned to the Dublin, Hilliard, New Albany-Plain, Westerville and Worthington school districts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] There are also several private schools in the area, such as St.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Paul's Lutheran School, a K-8 Christian school of the Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod in Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Some sources determine that the first kindergarten in the United States was established here by Louisa Frankenberg, a former student of Friedrich Fröbel.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Frankenberg immigrated to the city in 1838 and opened her kindergarten in the German Village neighborhood in that year.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The school did not work out, so she returned to Germany in 1840.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 1858, Frankenberg returned to Columbus and established another early kindergarten in the city.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Frankenberg is often overlooked, with Margarethe Schurz instead given credit for her "First Kindergarten" she operated for two years.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In addition, Indianola Junior High School (now the Graham Elementary and Middle School) became the nation's first junior high school in 1909, helping to bridge the difficult transition from elementary to high school at a time when only 48% of students continued their education after the ninth grade.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus Metropolitan Library (CML) has served central Ohio residents since 1873.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The system has 23 locations throughout Central Ohio, with a total collection of 3 million items.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] This library is one of the country's most-used library systems and is consistently among the top-ranked large city libraries according to Hennen's American Public Library Ratings.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] 1 library system in the nation in 1999, 2005 and 2008.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] It has been in the top four every year since 1999, when the rankings were first published in the *American Libraries* magazine, often challenging upstate neighbor Cuyahoga County Public Library for the top spot.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The classes of the Columbus Japanese Language School, a weekend Japanese school, are held in a facility from the school district in Marysville, while the school office is in Worthington.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Previously it held classes at facilities in the city of Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Several weekly and daily newspapers serve Columbus and Central Ohio.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The major daily newspaper in Columbus is *The Columbus Dispatch*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] There are also neighborhood- or suburb-specific papers, such as the Dispatch Printing Company's *ThisWeek Community News*, the *Columbus Messenger*, the *Clintonville Spotlight* and the *Short North Gazette*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] *The Lantern* and *1870* serve the Ohio State University community.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Alternative arts, culture or politics-oriented papers include *ALIVE* (formerly the independent *Columbus Alive* and now owned by the *Columbus Dispatch*), *Columbus Free Press* and *Columbus Underground* (digital-only).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The *Columbus Magazine*, *CityScene*, *614 Magazine* and *Columbus Monthly* are the city's magazines.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is the base for 12 television stations and is the 32nd-largest television market as of September 24, 2016.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is also home to the 36th-largest radio market.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Numerous medical systems operate in Columbus and Central Ohio.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Hospitals in Central Ohio are ranked favorably by the *U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] News & World Report*, where numerous hospitals are ranked as among the best in particular fields in the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Nationwide Children's is regarded as among the top 10 children's hospitals in the country, according to the report.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Electricity is distributed by Columbus Southern Power, an American Electric Power subsidiary.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Natural gas is provided by Columbia Gas of Ohio, while water is sourced from the City of Columbus Division of Water.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus's street system centers on its two main historic corridors, Broad and High Streets, which extend beyond the city limits; High Street is the longest in Columbus, running 13.5 mi (21.7 km) (23.4 across the county), while Broad Street is longer across the county, at 25.1 mi (40.4 km).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The street grid originates downtown, with High Street running north–south and Broad Street east–west; north–south streets are aligned 12 degrees west of due north, while avenues run similarly offset from due east–west.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city's address system begins at the intersection of Broad and High, with numbers increasing outward and even numbers on the north and east sides of streets.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Numbered avenues start 1+1⁄4 mi (2.0 km) north of Broad, while numbered streets begin around High Street and progress eastward.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] A difference of 700 house numbers equates to about 1 mi (1.6 km).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Other significant roads include Main Street, Morse Road, SR-161 (Dublin-Granville Road), SR-3 (Cleveland Avenue/Westerville Road), and Olentangy River Road.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus is bisected by two major Interstate Highways: Interstate 70 running east–west and Interstate 71 running north to roughly southwest.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] They combine downtown for about 1.5 mi (2.4 km) in an area locally known as "The Split", which is a major traffic congestion point, especially during rush hour.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Route 40, originally known as the National Road, runs east–west through Columbus, comprising Main Street to the east of downtown and Broad Street to the west.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Route 23 runs roughly north–south, while U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Due to its central location within Ohio and abundance of outbound roadways, nearly all of the state's destinations are within a two- or three-hour drive of Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Columbus riverfront hosts several bridges.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Discovery Bridge connects downtown to Franklinton across Broad Street.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The bridge opened in 1992, replacing a 1921 concrete arch bridge; the first bridge at the site was built in 1816.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The 700 ft (210 m) Main Street Bridge opened on July 30, 2010.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The bridge has three lanes for vehicular traffic (one westbound and two eastbound) and another separated lane for pedestrians and bikes.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Rich Street Bridge opened in July 2012 adjacent to the Main Street Bridge, connecting Rich Street on the east side of the river with Town Street on the west.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Lane Avenue Bridge is a cable-stayed bridge that opened on November 14, 2003, in the University District.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city's primary airport, John Glenn Columbus International Airport, is on the city's east side.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Formerly known as Port Columbus, John Glenn provides service to Toronto, Ontario, Canada, and Cancun, Mexico (on a seasonal basis), as well as to most domestic destinations, including all the major hubs along with San Francisco, Salt Lake City and Seattle.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The airport was a hub for discount carrier Skybus Airlines and continues to be home to NetJets, the world's largest fractional ownership air carrier.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] According to a 2005 market survey, John Glenn Columbus International Airport attracts about 50% of its passengers from outside of its 60-mile (97 km) radius primary service region.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] It is the 52nd-busiest airport in the United States by total passenger boardings.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Rickenbacker International Airport, in southern Franklin County, is a major cargo facility that is used by the Ohio Air National Guard.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Allegiant Air offers nonstop service from Rickenbacker to Florida destinations.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Ohio State University Don Scott Airport and Bolton Field are other large general-aviation facilities in the Columbus area.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 1907, 14-year-old Cromwell Dixon built the *SkyCycle,* a pedal-powered blimp, which he flew at Driving Park.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Three years later, one of the Wright brothers' exhibition pilots, Phillip Parmalee, conducted the world's first commercial cargo flight when he flew two packages containing 88 kilograms of silk 70 miles (110 km) from Dayton to Columbus in a Wright Model B.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] During World War I, six Columbus pilots, led by ace Eddie Rickenbacker, accounted for 10% of U.S. aerial victories, more than the aviators of any other American city.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] After the war, Columbus became a key hub in a transcontinental air-rail system, with Port Columbus Airport opening in 1929 following advocacy by Charles Lindbergh.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The inaugural TAT flight included Amelia Earhart, with Henry Ford and Harvey Firestone attending.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 1964, Columbus native Jerrie Mock became the first woman to fly solo around the world, setting a speed record in her plane, the *Spirit of Columbus*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus maintains a widespread municipal bus service called the Central Ohio Transit Authority (COTA).
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The service operates 41 routes with a fleet of 440 buses, serving approximately 19 million passengers per year.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] COTA operates 23 regular fixed-service routes, 14 express services, a bus rapid transit route, a free downtown circulator, night service, an airport connector and other services.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] LinkUS, an initiative between COTA, the city, and the Mid-Ohio Regional Planning Commission, is planning to add more rapid transit to Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Intercity bus service is provided at the Columbus Bus Station by Greyhound, Barons Bus Lines, Miller Transportation, GoBus and other carriers.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus does not have passenger rail service.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city's major train station, Union Station, was a stop along Amtrak's National Limited train service until 1977 and was razed in 1979, and the Greater Columbus Convention Center now stands in its place.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The station was also a stop along the Pennsylvania Railroad, the New York Central Railroad, the Chesapeake and Ohio Railway, the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, the Norfolk and Western Railway, the Cleveland, Columbus and Cincinnati Railroad, and the Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] As the city lacks local, commuter or intercity trains, Columbus is now the largest city and metropolitan area in the U.S. without any passenger rail service.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Cycling as transportation is steadily increasing in Columbus with its relatively flat terrain, intact urban neighborhoods, large student population and off-road bike paths.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city has put forth the 2012 Bicentennial Bikeways Plan, as well as a move toward a Complete Streets policy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Grassroots efforts such as Bike to Work Week, Consider Biking, Yay Bikes, Third Hand Bicycle Co-op, Franklinton Cycleworks and *Cranksters*, a local radio program focused on urban cycling, have contributed to cycling as transportation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The Main Street Bridge, opened in 2010, features a dedicated bike and pedestrian lane separated from traffic.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city also has its own public bicycle system.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] CoGo Bike Share has a network of about 600 bicycles and 80 docking stations.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] PBSC Urban Solutions, a company based in Canada, supplies technology and equipment.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Bird electric scooters have also been introduced.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The city of Columbus has a higher-than-average percentage of households without a car.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] In 2015, 9.8% of Columbus households lacked a car, a number that fell slightly to 9.4% in 2016.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus averaged 1.55 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus has 10 sister cities as designated by Sister Cities International.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] Columbus established its first sister city relationship in 1955 with Genoa, Italy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] To commemorate this relationship, Columbus received as a gift from the people of Genoa, a bronze statue of Christopher Columbus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/columbus-ohio-p02] The statue overlooked Broad Street in front of Columbus City Hall from 1955 to 2020; it was removed during the George Floyd protests.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Through a number of corporate mergers and acquisitions, Duracell came to be owned by the consumer products conglomerate Procter & Gamble (P&G).
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In November 2014, P&G reached an agreement to sell the company to the international conglomeration Berkshire Hathaway through a transfer of shares.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Under the deal, Berkshire Hathaway exchanged the shares it held in P&G for ownership of the Duracell business.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In 2025, alkaline batteries accounted for approximately 48% of the global primary battery market, and the alkaline battery market was valued at $9.75 billion.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell was one of the largest players, along with Energizer and Panasonic.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell originated via the partnership of scientist Samuel Ruben and businessman Philip Rogers Mallory, who met during the 1920s.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Mallory Company of Burlington, Massachusetts, United States, relocated its headquarters to Indianapolis, Indiana, in 1924.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] The company produced mercury batteries for military equipment, trumping the carbon-zinc batteries used then in virtually all applications.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Mallory & Co. acquired General Dry Batteries, Inc.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] (GDB) with headquarters in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] S. manufacturer of zinc-carbon batteries and had made mercury batteries under license from P.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Mallory during and post World War II until its acquisition in 1956.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] During the 1950s, Kodak introduced cameras with a bulb flash.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] The design required a new zinc-carbon cell size; AAA was introduced.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In 1960s, the term "Duracell" was introduced as a brand, from "durable cell".
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Until 1980, the batteries also bore the Mallory brand.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Mallory was acquired by Dart Industries in 1978, which in turn, merged with Kraft in 1980.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Kohlberg Kravis Roberts bought Duracell in 1988 and took the company public in 1989.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] It was acquired for $7 billion by The Gillette Company in 1996.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In 2005, Procter & Gamble acquired Duracell's parent Gillette for $57 billion.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In September 2011, Duracell and Powermat Technologies Ltd. started a joint venture, called Duracell Powermat, to make small wireless chargers for mobile phones and small electronics, with P&G owning 55% of the joint venture shares and Powermat 45%.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In March 2012, along with Powermat Technologies, Duracell, under the Procter & Gamble corporate umbrella, founded the Power Matters Alliance (PMA), an alliance of leading industry and governmental organizations that is dedicated to advancing smart and environmentally sound wireless power.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] AT&T and Starbucks joined the board later that year.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In 2013, the company released a "Duracell Quantum" line as their top-performing alkaline batteries.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] On October 24, 2014, Procter & Gamble announced it would spin off Duracell in 2015 as part of a wider restructuring scheme.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] On November 14, 2014, Berkshire Hathaway declared its intent to acquire Duracell in an all-stock deal, consisting of $4.7 billion worth of P&G stock then owned by Berkshire Hathaway.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] The acquisition received regulatory approval from the European Commission in July 2015.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] The transfer was completed on February 29, 2016, with P&G investing $1.8 billion in cash into Duracell, and Berkshire Hathaway giving P&G back 52 million shares.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In September 2016, Duracell announced plans to move its executive team and 60 employees to Chicago.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In July 2022, Duracell launched a home energy storage solution through California distributor Power Center+.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] The Duracell Power Center product line consists of 5 kW and 10 kW inverter products with lithium iron phosphate batteries that can be expanded from 14 kWh to 84 kWh.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Its Power Center AC connection allows new and existing solar owners to harvest excess solar energy for use when needed.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In February 2025, Duracell established its new global headquarters for research and development in Georgia, USA, with an investment of $56 million.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell manufactures alkaline batteries in many common sizes, such as AAA, AA, C, D, and 9V.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell entered into a brand licensing agreement with flash memory manufacturer Dane-Elec in 2008 for a line of products including memory cards, hard drives and USB flash drives with the Duracell brand mark and in the brand's trademark "copper top" coloring.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell also manufactures specialty batteries, including NiMH rechargeable batteries and batteries for cameras, watches, hearing aids, etc.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Their two main battery brands are "CopperTop (Plus)," marketed as longer-lasting, and "Ultra," directed mainly at users of digital devices and devices that need more power.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell also markets some lithium batteries and car batteries.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell manufactures alkaline and lithium batteries in prismatic as well as cylindrical shape.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In 2006, Duracell introduced "Power Pix" batteries with NiOx technology, designed to power digital cameras and other high-drain devices for up to twice as long as alkaline batteries.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell's professional batteries have been sold in the United States and Europe under the brand name "Procell" (previously "Industrial by Duracell" and "Duracell Procell").
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Two main product lines are currently sold under the Procell brand, "Procell Alkaline" and "Procell Intense Power", intended to provide longer endurance by tailoring the power profile of the batteries to the requirements of the device.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] "Procell Alkaline" are designed for use in low-drain applications such as clocks, and Procell Intense Power is designed for higher-drain devices.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In the 1980s, the company briefly had a line of flashlights called Durabeam, which was successful.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] In February 2022, Duracell announced a long-term partnership deal with Williams Racing.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] The deal culminated with the vertical air intake of the car designed like a Duracell battery, which was first introduced in the 2022 Miami Grand Prix.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] The design was later implemented on the Williams FW45 for the 2023 season.
[src:c-robert-kidder/duracell] Duracell also became the title sponsor of William Racing's eNASCAR team as Duracell Williams Esports eNASCAR.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The **Iowa State University of Science and Technology**, also referred to as **Iowa State University** (**Iowa State** or **ISU**), is a public land-grant research university in Ames, Iowa, United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Founded in 1858 as the **Iowa Agricultural College and Model Farm**, Iowa State became one of the nation's first designated land-grant institutions when the Iowa Legislature accepted the provisions of the 1862 Morrill Act on September 11, 1862.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] On July 4, 1959, the college was officially renamed Iowa State University of Science and Technology.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State is the largest university in Iowa by total enrollment.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] They offer more than 100 bachelor's degree programs, 120 master's degree programs, and 80 doctoral degree programs, plus a professional degree program in Veterinary Medicine.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State is classified among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity." The university is affiliated with the Ames National Laboratory, the Biorenewables Research Laboratory, the Plant Sciences Institute, and various other research institutes.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State University's athletic teams, the Cyclones, compete in Division I of the NCAA and are a founding member of the Big 12.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1856, the Iowa General Assembly enacted legislation to establish the Iowa Agricultural College and Model Farm.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] This institution (now Iowa State University) was officially established on March 22, 1858, by the General Assembly.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Story County was chosen as the location on June 21, 1859, beating proposals from Johnson, Kossuth, Marshall and Polk counties.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The original farm of 648 acres (2.62 km2) was purchased at a cost of $5,379.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa was the first state in the nation to accept the provisions of the Morrill Act of 1862.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The state subsequently designated Iowa State as the land-grant college on March 29, 1864.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State University is one of four universities that claims to be the first land-grant institution in the United States, the others being Kansas State University, Michigan State University, and the Pennsylvania State University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] From the start, Iowa Agricultural College focused on the ideals that higher education should be accessible to all and that the university should teach liberal and practical subjects.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] These ideals are integral to the land-grant university.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The institution has been coeducational since the first class admitted in 1868.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Formal admissions began the following year, and the first graduating class of 1872 consisted of 24 men and two women.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Farm House, the first building on the Iowa State campus, was completed in 1861 before the campus was occupied by students or classrooms.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It became the home of the superintendent of the Model Farm and in later years, the deans of Agriculture, including Seaman Knapp and James "Tama Jim" Wilson.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State's first president, Adonijah Welch, briefly stayed at the Farm House and penned his inaugural speech in a second floor bedroom.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Iowa Experiment Station was one of the university's prominent features.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Practical courses of instruction were taught, including one designed to give a general training for the career of a farmer.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Courses in mechanical, civil, electrical, and mining engineering were also part of the curriculum.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Roberts, professor of agriculture, held three-day farmers' institutes at Cedar Falls, Council Bluffs, Washington, and Muscatine.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] These became the earliest institutes held off-campus by a land grant institution and were the forerunners of 20th century extension.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1872, the first courses were given in domestic economy (home economics, family and consumer sciences) and were taught by Mary B.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State became the first land grant university to offer training in domestic economy for college credit.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1879, the School of Veterinary Science was organized, becoming the first state veterinary college in the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] This was originally a two-year course leading to a diploma.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The veterinary course of study contained classes in zoology, botany, anatomy of domestic animals, veterinary obstetrics, and sanitary science.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] William Miller Beardshear was appointed President of Iowa State in 1891.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] During his tenure, Iowa Agricultural College truly came of age.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Beardshear developed new agricultural programs and was instrumental in hiring premier faculty members such as Anson Marston, Louis B.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] He also expanded the university administration, and added Morrill Hall (1891), the Campanile (1899), Old Botany (now Carrie Chapman Catt Hall) (1892), and Margaret Hall (1895) to the campus, all of which stand today except for Margaret Hall, which was destroyed by a fire in 1938.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In his honor, Iowa State named its central administrative building (Central Building) after Beardshear in 1925.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1898, reflecting the school's growth during his tenure, it was renamed Iowa State College of Agricultural and Mechanic Arts, or Iowa State for short.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Today, Beardshear Hall holds the offices of the President, Vice-President, Treasurer, Secretary, Provost, and student financial aid.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Catt Hall is named after alumna and famed suffragette Carrie Chapman Catt, and is the home of the College of Liberal Arts and Sciences.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1912, Iowa State had its first Homecoming celebration.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The idea was first proposed by Professor Samuel Beyer, the college's "patron saint of athletics", who suggested that Iowa State inaugurate a celebration for alumni during the annual football game against rival University of Iowa.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Pearson, liked the idea and issued a special invitation to alumni two weeks prior to the event: "We need you, we must have you.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Come and see what a school you have made in Iowa State College.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Find a way." In October 2012 Iowa State marked its 100th Homecoming with a "CYtennial" Celebration.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State celebrated its first VEISHEA on May 11–13, 1922.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Wallace McKee (class of 1922) served as the first chairman of the Central Committee and Frank D.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Paine (professor of electrical engineering) chose the name, based on the first letters of Iowa State's colleges: Veterinary Medicine, Engineering, Industrial Science, Home Economics, and Agriculture.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] VEISHEA grew to become the largest student-run festival in the nation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Statistical Laboratory was established in 1933, with George W.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Snedecor, professor of mathematics, as the first director.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It was and is the first research and consulting institute of its kind in the country.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] While attempting to develop a faster method of computation, mathematics and physics professor John Vincent Atanasoff conceptualized the basic tenets of what would become the world's first electronic digital computer, the Atanasoff–Berry Computer (ABC), during a drive to Illinois in 1937.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] These included the use of a binary system of arithmetic, the separation of computer and memory functions, and regenerative drum memory, among others.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The 1939 prototype was constructed with graduate student Clifford Berry in the basement of the Physics Building.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] During World War II, Iowa State was one of 131 colleges and universities nationally that took part in the V-12 Navy College Training Program which offered students a path to a Navy commission.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] However, as a practical matter, the institution's name is simply Iowa State University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] By longstanding convention, the "Science and Technology" portion is omitted even in official documents, such as diplomas.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Official names given to the university's divisions were the College of Agriculture, College of Engineering, College of Home Economics, College of Sciences and Humanities, and College of Veterinary Medicine.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State's eight colleges today offer more than 100 undergraduate majors and 200 fields of study leading to graduate and professional degrees.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The academic program at ISU includes a liberal arts education and research in the biological and physical sciences.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The focus on technology has led directly to many research patents and inventions including the first binary computer, the ABC, Maytag blue cheese, and the round hay baler.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Located on a 2,000 acres (8.1 km2) campus, the university has grown considerably from its roots as an agricultural college and model farm and is recognized internationally today for its comprehensive research programs.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It continues to grow and set a new record for enrollment in the fall of 2015 with 36,001 students.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State played a role in the development of the atomic bomb during World War II as part of the Manhattan Project, a research and development program begun in 1942 under the Army Corps of Engineers.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The process to produce large quantities of high-purity uranium metal became known as the Ames process.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] One-third of the uranium metal used in the world's first controlled nuclear chain reaction was produced at Iowa State under the direction of Frank Spedding and Harley Wilhelm.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Ames Project received the Army/Navy E Award for Excellence in Production on October 12, 1945, for its work with metallic uranium as a vital war material.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Today, ISU is the only university in the United States that has a U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Department of Energy research laboratory physically located on its campus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State is the birthplace of the first electronic digital computer, starting the world's computer technology revolution.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Invented by mathematics and physics professor John Atanasoff and engineering graduate student Clifford Berry during 1937–42, the Atanasoff–Berry Computer pioneered important elements of modern computing.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Larson signed his decision following a lengthy court trial which declared the ENIAC patent of Mauchly and Eckert invalid and named Atanasoff the inventor of the electronic digital computer—the Atanasoff–Berry Computer or the ABC.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] An ABC Team consisting of Ames Laboratory and Iowa State engineers, technicians, researchers and students unveiled a working replica of the Atanasoff–Berry Computer in 1997 which can be seen on display on campus in the Durham Computation Center.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State's campus contains over 160 buildings.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Several buildings, as well as the Marston Water Tower, are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The central campus includes 490 acres (2.0 km2) of trees, plants, and classically designed buildings.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The landscape's most dominant feature is the 20-acre (81,000 m2) central lawn, which was listed as a "medallion site" by the American Society of Landscape Architects in 1999.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Thomas Gaines, in *The Campus As a Work of Art*, claimed that the Iowa State campus was one of the twenty-five most beautiful campuses in the country.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The campanile was constructed during 1897–1898 as a memorial to Margaret MacDonald Stanton, Iowa State's first dean of women, who died on July 25, 1895.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The tower is located on ISU's central campus, just north of the Memorial Union.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The site was selected by Margaret's husband, Edgar W.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Stanton, with the help of then-university president William M.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The campanile stands 110 feet (34 m) tall on a 16 by 16 foot (5 by 5 m) base, and cost $6,510.20 to construct.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The campanile is widely seen as one of the major symbols of Iowa State University.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It is featured prominently on the university's official ring and the university's mace, and is also the subject of the university's alma mater, *The Bells of Iowa State*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Noyes, who graduated in 1872, and later donated the funds to see that Alumni Hall could be completed after sitting unfinished and unused from 1905 to 1907.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Lake LaVerne is located west of the Memorial Union and south of Alumni Hall, Carver Hall, and Music Hall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Lake LaVerne is the home of two mute swans named Sir Lancelot and Elaine, donated to Iowa State by VEISHEA 1935.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1944, 1970, and 1971 cygnets (baby swans) made their home on Lake LaVerne.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Previously Sir Lancelot and Elaine were trumpeter swans but were too aggressive and in 1999 were replaced with two mute swans.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In early spring 2003, Lake LaVerne welcomed its newest and most current mute swan duo.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In support of Iowa Department of Natural Resources efforts to re-establish the trumpeter swans in Iowa, university officials avoided bringing breeding pairs of male and female mute swans to Iowa State which means the current Sir Lancelot and Elaine are both female.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State has maintained a horticulture garden since 1914.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Reiman Gardens is the third location for these gardens.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Today's gardens began in 1993 with a gift from Bobbi and Roy Reiman.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Construction began in 1994 and the Gardens' initial 5 acres (20,000 m2) were officially dedicated on September 16, 1995.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Reiman Gardens has since grown to become a 14 acres (57,000 m2) site consisting of a dozen distinct garden areas, an indoor conservatory and an indoor butterfly "wing", butterfly emergence cases, a gift shop, and several supporting greenhouses.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Located immediately south of Jack Trice Stadium on the ISU campus, Reiman Gardens is a year-round facility that has become one of the most visited attractions in central Iowa.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Gardens has received a number of national, state, and local awards since its opening, and its rose gardens are particularly noteworthy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The university museums consist of the Brunnier Art Museum, Farm House Museum, the Art on Campus Program, the Christian Petersen Art Museum, and the Elizabeth and Byron Anderson Sculpture Garden.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Brunnier Art Museum, Iowa's only accredited museum emphasizing a decorative arts collection, is one of the nation's few museums located within a performing arts and conference complex, the Iowa State Center.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Founded in 1975, the museum is named after its benefactors, Iowa State alumnus Henry J.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The decorative arts collection they donated, called the Brunnier Collection, is extensive, consisting of ceramics, glass, dolls, ivory, jade, and enameled metals.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Other fine and decorative art objects from the University Art Collection include prints, paintings, sculptures, textiles, carpets, wood objects, lacquered pieces, silver, and furniture.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] About eight to 12 annual changing exhibitions and permanent collection exhibitions provide educational opportunities.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Lectures, receptions, conferences, university classes, panel discussions, gallery walks, and gallery talks are presented to assist with further interpretation of objects.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Located near the center of the Iowa State campus, the Farm House Museum sits as a monument to early Iowa State history and culture as well as a National Historic Landmark.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] As the first building on campus, the Farm House was built in 1860 before campus was occupied by students or even classrooms.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The college's first farm tenants primed the land for agricultural experimentation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] This early practice lead to Iowa State Agricultural College and Model Farm opening its doors to Iowa students for free in 1869 under the Morrill Act (or Land-grant Act) of 1862.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Many prominent figures have made the Farm House their home throughout its 150 years of use.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The first president of the college, Adonijah Welch, briefly stayed at the Farm House and even wrote his inaugural speech in a bedroom on the second floor.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] James "Tama Jim" Wilson resided for much of the 1890s with his family at the Farm House until he joined President William McKinley's cabinet as U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Agriculture Dean Charles Curtiss and his young family replaced Wilson and became the longest resident of Farm House.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1976, over 110 years after the initial construction, the Farm House became a museum after much time and effort was put into restoring the early beauty of the modest farm home.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Today, faculty, students, and community members can enjoy the museum while honoring its significance in shaping a nationally recognized land-grant university.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Its collection boasts a large collection of 19th and early 20th century decorative arts, furnishings and material culture reflecting Iowa State and Iowa heritage.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Objects include furnishings from Carrie Chapman Catt and Charles Curtiss, a wide variety of quilts, a modest collection of textiles and apparel, and various china and glassware items.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Farm House Museum is an on-campus educational resource providing a changing environment of exhibitions among the historical permanent collection objects that are on display.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State is home to one of the largest campus public art programs in the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Over 2,000 works of public art, including 600 by significant national and international artists, are located across campus in buildings, courtyards, open spaces and offices.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] He also offered Christian Petersen a one-semester sculptor residency to design and build the fountain and bas relief at the Dairy Industry Building.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1955, 21 years later, Petersen retired having created 12 major sculptures for the campus and hundreds of small studio sculptures.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Art on Campus Collection is a campus-wide resource of over 2000 public works of art.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Programs, receptions, dedications, university classes, Wednesday Walks, and educational tours are presented on a regular basis.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Christian Petersen Art Museum in Morrill Hall is named for the nation's first permanent campus artist-in-residence, Christian Petersen, who sculpted and taught at Iowa State from 1934 through 1955, and is considered the founding artist of the Art on Campus Collection.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Named for Justin Smith Morrill who created the Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act, Morrill Hall was completed in 1891.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Originally constructed to fill the capacity of a library, museum, and chapel, its original uses are engraved in the exterior stonework on the east side.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The building was vacated in 1996 when it was determined unsafe and was also listed in the National Register of Historic Places the same year.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2005, $9 million was raised to renovate the building and convert it into a museum.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Completed and reopened in March 2007, Morrill Hall is home to the Christian Petersen Art Museum.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] As part of University Museums, the Christian Petersen Art Museum at Morrill Hall is the home of the Christian Petersen Art Collection, the Art on Campus Program, the University Museums's Visual Literacy and Learning Program, and Contemporary Changing Art Exhibitions Program.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Located within the Christian Petersen Art Museum are the Lyle and Nancy Campbell Art Gallery, the Roy and Bobbi Reiman Public Art Studio Gallery, the Margaret Davidson Center for the Study of the Art on Campus Collection, the Edith D. and Torsten E.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Lagerstrom Loaned Collections Center, and the Neva M.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] University Museums shares the James R. and Barbara R.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Palmer Small Objects Classroom in Morrill Hall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Elizabeth and Byron Anderson Sculpture Garden is located by the Christian Petersen Art Museum at historic Morrill Hall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The sculpture garden design incorporates sculptures, a gathering arena, and sidewalks and pathways.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Planted with perennials, ground cover, shrubs, and flowering trees, the landscape design provides a setting for works of 20th and 21st century sculpture, primarily American.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Ranging from forty-four inches to nearly nine feet high and from bronze to other metals, these works of art represent both modern and contemporary sculpture.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The sculpture garden is adjacent to Iowa State's 22 acres (89,000 m2) central campus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State's composting facility is capable of processing over 10,000 tons of organic waste every year.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The school's $3 million revolving loan fund loans money for energy efficiency and conservation projects on campus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In the 2011 College Sustainability Report Card issued by the Sustainable Endowments Institute, the university received a B grade.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State University is organized into eight colleges and two schools that offer 100 Bachelor's degree programs, 112 Masters programs, and 83 Ph.D programs, including one professional degree program in Veterinary Medicine.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Classified as one of Carnegie's "R1: Doctoral Universities - Very High Research Activity," Iowa State received nearly $550 million in research grants for fiscal year 2025.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Robert and Ellen Sorge Parks Library contains over 2.6 million books and subscribes to more than 98,600 journal titles.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Robert Parks (1915–2003), the 11th president of Iowa State University, and his wife, Ellen Sorge Parks, the original library was built in 1925 with three subsequent additions made in 1961, 1969, and 1983.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The library was dedicated and named after W.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Surrounding the first floor lobby staircase in Parks Library are eight mural panels designed by Iowa artist Grant Wood.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The cooperative extension service traces its roots to farmers' institutes developed at Iowa State in the late 19th century.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Committed to community, Iowa State pioneered the outreach mission of being a land-grant college through creation of the first Extension Service in 1902.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 1906, the Iowa Legislature enacted the Agricultural Extension Act making funds available for demonstration projects.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It is believed this was the first specific legislation establishing state extension work, for which Iowa State assumed responsibility.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The national extension program was created in 1914 based heavily on the Iowa State model.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State University is a member of the Universities Research Association, University Corporation for Atmospheric Research and the Association of Public and Land-grant Universities.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In fiscal year 2023, Iowa State spent $420.8 million in R&D.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State was a member of the Association of American Universities from 1958 until April 2022.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It departed claiming that AAU's internal ranking indicators unfairly favor institutions with high levels of NIH funding and noted that its strength is not in biomedical research because the school does not have a medical school.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State is the only university in the United States that has a U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Operated by Iowa State, Ames National Laboratory is one of ten national DOE Office of Science research laboratories.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] ISU research for the government provided Ames National Laboratory its start in the 1940s with the development of a highly efficient process for producing high-purity uranium for atomic energy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Ames National Laboratory employs more than 500 full- and part-time employees.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Students make up more than 45 percent of the paid workforce.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Dan Shechtman, awarded the 2011 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the discovery of quasicrystals at Johns Hopkins University, is an Associate of Ames National Laboratory.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The ISU Research Park Corporation was established in 1987 as a not-for-profit, independent, corporation operating under a board of directors appointed by Iowa State University and the ISU Foundation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The corporation manages both the Research Park and incubator programs.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2010, the **Biorenewables Research Laboratory** opened in a LEED-Gold certified building that complements and helps replace labs and offices across Iowa State and promotes interdisciplinary, systems-level research and collaboration.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Lab houses the Bioeconomy Institute, the Biobased Industry Center, and the National Science Foundation Engineering Research Center for Biorenewable Chemicals, a partnership of six universities as well as the Max Planck Society in Germany and the Technical University of Denmark.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The **Engineering Teaching and Research Complex** was built in 1999 and is home to Stanley and Helen Howe Hall and Gary and Donna Hoover Hall.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] And the complex contains one of the world's only six-sided immersive virtual reality labs (C6), as well as the 240 seat 3D-capable Alliant Energy Lee Liu Auditorium, the Multimodal Experience Testbed and Laboratory (METaL), and the User Experience Lab (UX Lab).
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] All of which supports the research of more than 50 faculty and 200 graduate, undergraduate, and postdoctoral students.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The **Plant Sciences Institute** was founded in 1999.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] PSI's research focus is to understand the effects of genotype (genetic makeup) and environment on phenotypes (traits) sufficiently well that it will be able to predict the phenotype of a given genotype in a given environment.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Carver Co-Laboratory and is home to the Plant Sciences Institute Faculty Scholars program.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] There is also the Iowa State University Northeast Research Farm in Nashua.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State operates 20 on-campus residence halls.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The residence halls are divided into geographical areas.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Union Drive Association (UDA) consists of four residence halls located on the west side of campus, including Friley Hall, which has been declared one of the largest residence halls in the country.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Richardson Court Association (RCA) consists of 12 residence halls on the east side of campus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Towers Residence Association (TRA) are located south of the main campus.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Two of the four towers, Knapp and Storms Halls, were imploded in 2005; however, Wallace and Wilson Halls still stand.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Buchanan Hall and Geoffroy Hall are nominally considered part of the RCA, despite their distance from the other buildings.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] ISU operates two apartment complexes for upperclassmen, Frederiksen Court and SUV Apartments.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The governing body for ISU students is the ISU Student Government.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The ISU Student Government is composed of a president, vice president, finance director, cabinet appointed by the president, a clerk appointed by the vice president, senators representing each college and residence area at the university, a nine-member judicial branch, and an election commission.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] ISU has over 900 student organizations on campus that represent a variety of interests.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Organizations are supported by Iowa State's Student Engagement Office.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Many student organization offices are housed in the Memorial Union.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Memorial Union at Iowa State University opened in September 1928 and is currently home to a number of University departments and student organizations, The M-Shop, CyBowl & Billiards, the University Book Store, and the Workspace.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The original building was designed by architect, William T.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The building employs a classical style of architecture reflecting Greek and Roman influences.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The building's design specifically complements the designs of the major buildings surrounding the University's Central Campus area, Beardshear Hall to the west, Curtiss Hall to the east, and MacKay Hall to the north.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The style utilizes columns with Corinthian capitals, Palladian windows, triangular pediments, and formally balanced facades.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Designed to be a living memorial for ISU students lost in World War I, the building includes a solemn memorial hall, named the Gold Star Room, which honors the names of the dead World War I, World War II, Korean, Vietnam, and war on terrorism veterans engraved in marble.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Symbolically, the hall was built directly over a library (the Browsing Library) and a small chapel, the symbol being that no country would ever send its young men to die in a war for a noble cause without a solid foundation on both education (the library) and religion (the chapel).
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] On Veterans Day in 2014, ISU's "Gold Star Hall" publicly honored Petty Officer Jerry Leroy Converse, a U.S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Navy sailor that was killed by Israel during the 1967 USS *Liberty* incident.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Converse is buried at Oak Hill Cemetery in Cherokee, Iowa.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] This ceremony came 47 years after the attack.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Renovations and additions have continued through the years to include: elevators, bowling lanes, a parking ramp, a book store, food court, and additional wings.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Fraternities and sororities at ISU include fifty chapters that involve 14.6 percent of undergraduate students.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Collectively, fraternity and sorority members have raised over $82,000 for philanthropies and committed 31,416 hours to community service.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2006, the ISU Greek community was named the best large Greek community in the Midwest.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The first fraternity, Delta Tau Delta, was established at Iowa State in 1875, six years after the first graduating class entered Iowa State.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Sorocis, was established two years later, in 1877.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Sorocis later became a chapter of the first national sorority at Iowa State, Pi Beta Phi.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] President Storms lifted the ban in 1904.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Following the lifting of the fraternity ban, thirteen national fraternities were installed on the Iowa State campus between 1904 and 1913.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The *Iowa State Daily* is the university's student newspaper.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The *Daily* has its roots from a news sheet titled the *Clipper*, which was started in the spring of 1890 by a group of students at Iowa Agricultural College led by F.E.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The *Clipper* soon led to the creation of the *Iowa Agricultural College Student*, and the beginnings of what would one day become the *Iowa State Daily*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It was awarded the 2016 Best All-Around Daily Student Newspaper by the Society of Professional Journalists.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] 88.5 KURE is the university's student-run radio station.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] ISUtv is the university's student-run television station.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It is housed in the former WOI-TV station that was established in 1950.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State is widely known for VEISHEA, an annual education and entertainment festival that was held on campus each spring.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The name VEISHEA was derived from the initials of ISU's five original colleges, forming an acronym as the university existed when the festival was founded in 1922.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] VEISHEA was the largest student-run festival in the nation, bringing in tens of thousands of visitors to the campus each year.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] VEISHEA was retired as an annual event at Iowa State in 2014.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The celebration featured an annual parade and many open-house demonstrations of the university facilities and departments.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Campus organizations exhibited products, technologies, and held fund raisers for various charity groups.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] That year, Iowa suffered an unusually high number of devastating cyclones (as tornadoes were called at the time).
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In September, Iowa Agricultural College's football team traveled to Northwestern University and defeated that team by a score of 36–0.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The next day, the *Chicago Tribune'*s headline read "Struck by a Cyclone: It Comes from Iowa and Devastates Evanston Town." The article began, "Northwestern might as well have tried to play football with an Iowa cyclone as with the Iowa team it met yesterday." The nickname stuck.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The school colors are cardinal and gold.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The mascot is Cy the Cardinal, introduced in 1954.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Since a cyclone was determined to be difficult to depict in costume, the cardinal was chosen in reference to the school colors.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] A contest was held to select a name for the mascot, with the name Cy being chosen as the winner.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Iowa State Cyclones are a member of the Big 12 Conference and compete in NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS), fielding 16 varsity teams in 12 sports.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Cyclones also compete in and are a founding member of the Central States Collegiate Hockey League of the American Collegiate Hockey Association.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State's intrastate archrival is the University of Iowa with whom it competes annually for the Iowa Corn Cy-Hawk Series trophy, an annual athletic competition between the two schools.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Sponsored by the Iowa Corn Growers Association, the competition includes all head-to-head regular season competitions between the two rival universities in all sports.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Football first made its way onto the Iowa State campus in 1878 as a recreational sport, but it was not until 1892 that Iowa State organized its first team to represent the school in football.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Beardshear spearheaded the foundation of an athletic association to officially sanction Iowa State football teams.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Cyclones compete each year for traveling trophies.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Since 1977, Iowa State and Iowa compete annually for the Cy-Hawk Trophy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State competes in an annual rivalry game against Kansas State known as Farmageddon and against former conference foe Missouri for the Telephone Trophy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Cyclones also compete against the Iowa Hawkeyes, their in-state rival.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Cyclones play their home games at Jack Trice Stadium, named after Jack Trice, ISU's first African-American athlete and also the first and only Iowa State athlete to die from injuries sustained during athletic competition.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Trice died three days after his first game playing for Iowa State against Minnesota in Minneapolis on October 6, 1923.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Suffering from a broken collarbone early in the game, he continued to play until he was trampled by a group of Minnesota players.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] It is disputed whether he was trampled purposely or if it was by accident.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The stadium was named in his honor in 1997 and is the only NCAA Division I-A stadium named after an African-American.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Jack Trice Stadium, formerly known as Cyclone Stadium, opened on September 20, 1975, with a win against the United States Air Force Academy.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Hopes of "Hilton Magic" returning took a boost with the hiring of ISU alum, Ames native, and fan favorite Fred Hoiberg as coach of the men's basketball team in April 2010.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Hoiberg ("The Mayor") played three seasons under legendary coach Johnny Orr and one season under future Chicago Bulls coach Tim Floyd during his standout collegiate career as a Cyclone (1991–95).
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Orr laid the foundation of success in men's basketball upon his arrival from Michigan in 1980 and is credited with building Hilton Magic.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Besides Hoiberg, other Cyclone greats played for Orr and brought winning seasons, including Jeff Grayer, Barry Stevens, and walk-on Jeff Hornacek.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The 1985-86 Cyclones were one of the most memorable.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Orr coached the team to second place in the Big Eight and produced one of his greatest career wins, a victory over his former team and No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] 2 seed Michigan in the second round of the NCAA tournament.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Under coaches Floyd (1995–98) and Larry Eustachy (1998–2003), Iowa State achieved even greater success.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Floyd took the Cyclones to the Sweet Sixteen in 1997 and Eustachy led ISU to two consecutive Big 12 regular season conference titles in 1999-2000 and 2000–01, plus the conference tournament title in 2000.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] 2 in the 2000 NCAA tournament, Eustachy and the Cyclones defeated UCLA in the Sweet Sixteen before falling to Michigan State, the eventual NCAA Champion, in the regional finals by a score of 75–64 (the differential representing the Spartans' narrowest margin of victory in the tournament).
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Standout Marcus Fizer and Jamaal Tinsley were scoring leaders for the Cyclones who finished the season 32–5.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Tinsley returned to lead the Cyclones the following year with another conference title and No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] 2 seed, but ISU finished the season with a 25–6 overall record after a stunning loss to No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2011–12, Hoiberg's Cyclones finished third in the Big 12 and returned to the NCAA tournament, dethroning defending national champion Connecticut, 77–64, in the second round before losing in the Round of 32 to top-seeded Kentucky.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] All-Big 12 First Team selection Royce White led the Cyclones with 38 points and 22 rebounds in the two contests, ending the season at 23–11.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The 2013-14 campaign turned out to be another highly successful season.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State went 28–8, won the Big 12 Tournament, and advanced to the Sweet Sixteen by beating North Carolina in the second round of the NCAA tournament.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Cyclones finished 11–7 in Big 12 play, finishing in a tie for third in the league standings, and beat a school-record nine teams (9–3) that were ranked in the Associated Press top 25.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Cyclones opened the season 14–0, breaking the school record for consecutive wins.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Melvin Ejim was named the Big 12 Player of the Year and an All-American by five organizations.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Deandre Kane was named the Big 12 Tournament's most valuable player.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] On June 8, 2015, Steve Prohm took over as head basketball coach replacing Hoiberg who left to take the head coaching position with the Chicago Bulls.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In his first season with the Cyclones, Prohm secured a #4 seed in the Midwest region where the Cyclones advanced to the Sweet Sixteen before falling to top-seeded Virginia, 84–71.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2017, Iowa State stunned 3rd ranked Kansas, 92–89, in overtime, snapping KU's 54-game home winning streak, before winning the 2017 Big 12 men's basketball tournament, its third conference championship in four years, defeating West Virginia in the final.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Of Iowa State's 19 NCAA tournament appearances, the Cyclones have reached the Sweet Sixteen eight times (1986, 1997, 2000, 2014, 2016, 2022, 2024, 2026), made two appearances in the Elite Eight (1944, 2000), and reached the Final Four once in 1944.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Iowa State is known for having one of the most successful women's basketball programs in the nation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Since the founding of the Big 12, Coach Bill Fennelly and the Cyclones have won three conference titles (one regular season, two tournament), and have advanced to the Sweet Sixteen five times (1999–2001, 2009, 2010) and the Elite Eight twice (1999, 2009) in the NCAA tournament.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The team has one of the largest fan bases in the nation with attendance figures ranked third in the nation in 2009, 2010, 2012, 2016, 2017, and 2020 and second in the nation in 2013, 2014, 2018 and 2022.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Coach Christy Johnson-Lynch led the 2012 Cyclones team to a fifth straight 20-win season and fifth NCAA regional semifinal appearance in six seasons, and leading Iowa State to a 22–8 (13–3 Big 12) overall record and second-place finish in the conference.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Cyclones finished the season with seven wins over top-25 teams, including a victory over No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] 1 Nebraska Cornhuskers in Iowa State's first-ever win over a top-ranked opponent in addition to providing the only Big 12 Conference loss to the 2012 conference and NCAA champion Texas Longhorns.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2011, Iowa State finished the season 25–6 (13–3 Big 12), placing second in the league, as well as a final national ranking of eighth.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] 2011 is only the second season in which an Iowa State volleyball team has ever recorded 25 wins.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] 9 Florida during the season in Gainesville, its sixth win over a top-10 team in Cyclone history.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2009, Iowa State finished the season second in the Big 12 behind Texas with a 27–5 record and ranked No.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Johnson-Lynch is the fastest Iowa State coach to clinch 100 victories.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2011, she became the school's winningest volleyball coach when her team defeated the Texas Tech Red Raiders, her 136th coaching victory, in straight sets.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The ISU wrestling program has captured the NCAA wrestling tournament title eight times between 1928 and 1987, and won the Big 12 Conference Tournament three consecutive years, 2007–2009.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] On February 7, 2010, the Cyclones became the first collegiate wrestling program to record its 1,000th dual win in program history by defeating the Arizona State Sun Devils, 30–10, in Tempe, Arizona.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] Dan Gable, another legendary ISU wrestler, is famous for having lost only one match in his entire Iowa State collegiate career - his last - and winning gold at the 1972 Olympics in Munich, Germany, while not giving up a single point.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In 2013, Iowa State hosted its eighth NCAA Wrestling Championships.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] The Cyclones hosted the first NCAA championships in 1928.
[src:c-robert-kidder/iowa-state-university] In February 2017, former Virginia Tech coach and 2016 NWCA Coach of the Year Kevin Dresser was introduced as the new Cyclone wrestling coach, replacing Kevin Jackson.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha was founded at Boston University in 1909.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] It is a member of the North American Interfraternity Conference (NIC), which it rejoined in November 2023 after withdrawing from the conference in 2015.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Among the largest 15 social fraternities in the world, Lambda Chi Alpha is the youngest.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Since 2014, after maintaining its headquarters at various locations in Indiana, Massachusetts, and Pennsylvania, it has been headquartered in Carmel, Indiana, outside Indianapolis.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha was founded by Warren A.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Cole, a law student at Boston University School of Law in Boston.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] There are two different accounts of the fraternity's founding.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The official story told by Cole and Albert Cross is that on November 2, 1909, Cole, Percival C.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Nichols reorganized the Cosmopolitan Law Club, a society of Boston University law students into the Loyal Collegiate Associates, which was renamed Lambda Chi Alpha in 1912.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] All were close friends and had been members of Alpha Mu Chi, a prep school fraternity.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The Greek letter name is thought to have been used from the beginning but is not recorded in the *Alpha Zeta* minutes until April 27, 1910.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] A second account of the founding, based on interviews with contemporaries, is that Cole and others did belong to a loose group known as the Tombs or Cosmopolitan Club but this was not related to Lambda Chi Alpha's founding.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Instead, according to the alternative account, Cole shared an apartment with James C.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Proctor, who later joined Sigma Alpha Epsilon.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Cole then established his own fraternity with Ralph S.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The group issued a charter for itself that was backdated to November 15.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Cole approached many local groups at colleges and universities throughout the Northeast seeking others willing to join his new fraternity.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] He corresponded with or visited 117 institutions by 1912, when a group at Massachusetts Agricultural College accepted a charter to become *Gamma Zeta*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The first General Assembly, establishing a structure for the national fraternity, was held in Boston on April 13, 1912.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The fraternity held its second general assembly in Boston on March 22, 1913 in which the fraternity adopted its secret motto, ritual insignia including its badge and coat of arms, and the basic organizational structure.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha virtually replaced the fraternity Cole had established outside of its name.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The 14th General Assembly, in 1931, recognized March 22 as Lambda Chi Alpha Day in recognition of these achievements.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 1942, the board of directors renamed it Founder's Day.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] November 2, 1909 is also still recognized, so Lambda Chi Alpha celebrates two Founders Days annually.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In the years that followed, a divide opened between Cole and a group of young alumni led by Mason, Ernst J.C.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Fischer of Lambda Chi's Cornell University chapter in Ithaca, New York, and Samuel Dyer of the University of Maine chapter in Orono, Maine.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Dyer was supported by Albert Cross at the University of Pennsylvania chapter in Philadelphia and Louis Robbins of the Brown University chapter in Providence, Rhode Island.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 1920, Cole was ousted and Fischer was elected national president.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 1927, Fischer became international president when *Epsilon-Epsilon Zeta* at the University of Toronto in Toronto was chartered.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The Theta Kappa Nu fraternity was formed by eleven local fraternities on June 9, 1924, in Springfield, Missouri.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] With the help of the North American Interfraternity Conference in identifying local groups, and Theta Kappa Nu's policy of granting charters quickly to organizations with good academic standards, the fraternity grew quickly and had approximately 2,500 initiates in 40 chapters by the end of 1926.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] During the Great Depression, both Theta Kappa Nu and Lambda Chi Alpha saw membership decrease and chapters shut down.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 1939, the two fraternities agreed to merge.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The merger ceremony was held at Howard College (now Samford University) chapter of Theta Kappa Nu in Birmingham, Alabama.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The merger immediately increased the number of chapters from 77 to 105 (or 78 to 106) and the number of members from 20,000 to 27,000.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] At the time, this was the largest merger in fraternity history.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] All Theta Kappa Nu chapters became Lambda Chi Alpha chapters and were given chapter designations that began with either Theta, Kappa, or Nu.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] At schools where chapters of both fraternities previously existed, the two merged and retained Lambda Chi's Zeta recognition.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha was founded in Boston, Massachusetts, in 1909.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] For the first decade of its existence, the fraternity lacked a central office and records were divided between the homes of Grand High Alpha Warren A.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Cole in Swansea, Massachusetts and Registrar Samuel Dyer in Attleboro, Massachusetts.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 1920, the fraternity moved its headquarters to Northeastern Pennsylvania, where it was located in Kingston and Wilkes Barre.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Later that year, it relocated to Indianapolis, where many other fraternity and sorority national headquarters are located.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Since 2021, its headquarters has been based in Carmel, Indiana, outside Indianapolis.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The fraternity first joined the North American Interfraternity Conference (NIC) in 1913.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In October 2015, it resigned from the association, citing in-fighting and dysfunctional governance.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The fraternity's exit coincided with NIC lobbying for the Safe Campus Act, which was opposed by both the fraternity and sexual assault advocacy groups.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha re-joined the NIC in November 2023.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The colors of Lambda Chi Alpha are royal purple, kelly green, and old gold.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Its flower is the white rose and its mascot is the lion rampant.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Its motto is **Vir Quisque Vir** or "Every Man a Man." The fraternity's core values or pillars are Loyalty, Duty, Respect, Service & Stewardship, Honor, Integrity, Personal Courage.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Beginning in August 1969, the concept of fraternity education replaced pledge education at Lambda Chi Alpha.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The fraternity education program was designed to integrate all new members into the chapter equally.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 1972, Lambda Chi Alpha officially abolished the pledge process and replaced it with associate membership.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Associate members in Lambda Chi Alpha to this day have all of the same rights as initiated brothers, can hold officer positions, wear the letters, and can vote on all issues except for those involving Lambda Chi's initiation ritual.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Status as an associate member permits new members to enter the fraternity with respect, and helps to combat the issues that arise from the possible abuse of pledges.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha was the first fraternal organization to abolish pledging.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] From 1993 to 2012, Lambda Chi Alpha's philanthropy was the North American Food Drive (NAFD).
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] As of 2010, NAFD had collected around 33 million pounds of food for food banks.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 2012, NAFD was discontinued under that name and rolled into an ongoing partnership with Feeding America.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 2017, Lambda Chi Alpha announced a trial partnership with the St.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Baldrick's Foundation, a Monrovia, California-based organization that funds childhood cancer research.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Chapters were encouraged to host or participate in head-shaving events to raise money for the foundation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 2019, Lambda Chi Alpha announced a partnership with The Jed Foundation, a Boston-based non-profit organization that seeks to protect emotional health and prevent suicide for teens and young adults.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Together, they are launching Lambda Chi Alpha Lifeline, an online mental health resource center tailored from the foundation's ULifeline website, which provides college students with information about emotional health issues and specific resources available to them on their respective campuses.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] It also offers a confidential mental health self-screening tool.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 2020, Lambda Chi Alpha announced its partnership with Movember, an Australia-based non-profit foundation that raises awareness of men's health issues such as prostate cancer, testicular cancer, and men's suicide.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Movember has recently become a primary philanthropic focus for Lambda Chi Alpha and the fraternity's national administrative office.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 2023, Lambda Chi Alpha announced its partnership with American Red Cross, a nonprofit humanitarian organization that provides emergency assistance, disaster relief, and disaster preparedness education in the United States.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha is the first and only fraternity with a partnership with The American Red Cross.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] As of 2024, Lambda Chi Alpha reported 185 active chapters and associate chapters, representing universities in most U.S. states and three Canadian provinces.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha is atypical in its naming scheme.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Unlike most fraternities, the order in which chapters are named is not strictly based on the Greek alphabet.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Instead, Lambda Chi Alpha chapters are known as Zetas.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] As such, for instance, the Alpha-Beta chapter is designated Alpha-Beta Zeta.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In addition, since the fraternity's founding, Cole assigned Greek letters to petitioning groups that had not yet been chartered.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Not all of these groups were chartered, however.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] As a result, the first 22 chapters were designated Α, Γ, Ε, Ζ, Ι, Λ, Β, Σ, Φ, Δ, Π, Ο, Μ, Τ, Η, Θ, Υ, Ξ, Χ, Ω, Κ, Ν, Ρ, Ψ.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] When Theta Kappa Nu merged with Lambda Chi Alpha in 1939, the former Theta Kappa Nu chapters were each given chapter designations prefixed with Θ, Κ, or Ν.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The second letter of their chapter name was assigned in the order mentioned above and applied to the chapters in order of their precedence in Theta Kappa Nu.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] On campuses with chapters of both Lambda Chi Alpha and Theta Kappa Nu, the chapter of Lambda Chi Alpha kept its original designation.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] A singular exception was the chapter at Georgia Tech in Atlanta, *Β-Κ Zeta*, which was named in recognition of its existence as a chapter of the Beta Kappa, a national fraternity whose other existing chapters merged with Theta Chi in 1942.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Lambda Chi Alpha has over 300,000 members.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Truman, the 33rd president of the United States, was made an honorary initiate of the Lambda Chi Alpha chapter at the University of Missouri.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 2023, the University of New Orleans chapter was featured in Season Seven, Episode 1 of the Netflix series, *Queer Eye*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In October 1958, a Lambda Chi pledge at MIT, Oliver R.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Smoot, gained global recognition when his MIT fraternity brothers had him lay down repeatedly on Harvard Bridge between Boston and Cambridge while they measured the bridge using his height, which turned out to be 5 feet 7 inches.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] Smoot's height was defined as one "smoot", and Harvard Bridge was officially measured as 364.4 smoots (2,035 ft; 620.1 m) smoots long.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The measurement is commemorated with a plaque on Harvard Bridge describing the incident.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 2009, in remembrance and celebration of the legacy of Smoot, the Pennsylvania Western University, Edinboro chapter contributed to funding the construction of a pickleball facility in collaboration with the university.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] The addition comprised a total square smootage of 46,735.8 square smoots (1,456,923.65 sq ft).
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In 2011, the word "smoot" and its definition were added to the fifth edition of the *American Heritage Dictionary*.
[src:c-robert-kidder/lambda-chi-alpha] In October 1958, the fraternity expelled its Hamilton College chapter in Clinton, New York, for insisting on a non-discrimination policy for admitting members.
